<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latvia's Top Legislator Criticizes Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior Latvian legislator has
accused Russia of "political blackmail" and seeking to hinder the
small Baltic nation's development.
</P>
<P>
Latvia wanted to maintain good relations with Russia but found
unacceptable Russia's "patronage and political blackmail,
resembling the notorious role of the elder brother", said Latvian
parliament speaker Alfreds Cepanis, according to Interfax news
agency.
</P>
<P>
Cepanis, at a ceremonial parliamentary meeting to mark the
eighth anniversary of the adoption of the former Soviet republic's
declaration of independence, criticized Russia for creating a
certain international isolation of the Baltic state and slowing
down its advance towards the European Union and NATO.
</P>
<P>
However, Cepanis said Latvia was ready for an open dialogue
with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Russia and Latvia turned tense when Latvian
police forcefully disbanded a rally by Russian-speaking pensioners
in Riga in early March, triggering a backlash from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Some 700,000 Russian-speaking people are living in Latvia,
accounting for one-third of the country's population, but only
4,000 have received Latvian nationality.
</P>
<P>
Cepanis said that Russia had reacted inadequately to events
and unleashed a campaign against Latvia, including insulting
comments by Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
He claimed the tone and form of Russian statements and the
threat of economic sanctions were unacceptable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
