<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Levies Excise Duty on Imported Beverages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has levied
excise tariffs on imported beverages one month after it lifted a
ban on these commodities, the East African paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The affected goods include soft drinks, beer and car
batteries.
</P>
<P>
The Commissioner for Taxation in the Ministry of Finance, Mr.
K. Kiiza, said that an excise duty of 230 and 650 Uganda
Shillings (0.2 and 0.6 U.S. Dollars) would be introduced on every
liter of imported soda and beer respectively.
</P>
<P>
A 17 percent valued added tax and 12 percent COMESA (Common
Market for East and Southern Africa) duty, he added, will also be
put on these imports.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a finance official as saying: "the new tariff
schedule is meant to protect our industries or at least to put
imports at par with locally produced products."
</P>
<P>
Some businesses, however, rapped the measure, saying it just
made imported beverages more expensive than local ones.
</P>
<P>
The recent lifting of the beer ban sparked concern among beer
manufacturers here. The Kampala-based Uganda Breweries Limited
and Nile Breweries Limited, the two beer manufacturers in the
country, have invested in plant expansion in an effort to
increase production capacity and competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
