<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-04 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanians Leave for Kuwait to Visit Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-six Jordanians left here on
Monday for Kuwait to meet with their loved ones currently jailed
in the Gulf sheikdom.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanians, mostly spouses and children of the prisoners,
will stay in Kuwait for three days, Mu'in Qassis, spokesman for
the Amman Office of the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC) told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The trip came after Kuwait pardoned 13 Jordanian prisoners on
April 27 in a moved aime at improving bilateral relations. The 13
Jordanians have not returned to Jordan yet.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 Jordanians were sentenced by Kuwaiti security courts on
charges of collaborating with Iraq during its seven-month
occupation of Kuwait from August 1990 to February 1991.
</P>
<P>
"This is the fourth ICRC-sponsored visit since the end of the
Gulf War (in 1991)," Qassis said. The previous visits took place
in June and September 1995 and January 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Through these trips, the ICRC has enabled 133 Jordanians to
meet with relatives detained in Kuwait," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Jordan-Kuwait relations soured due to Jordan's perceived
tilt toward Iraq during its occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have been inching for reconciliation,
especially since Jordan distanced itself from the Iraqi
leadership. But their diplomatic relationship has not been fully
restored. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
