<HEADLINE> Hamas Leader Winds up Visit to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The founder and spiritual leader of
the Palestinian Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) Sheikh Ahmad
Yassin wound up his six-day visit here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Iran's official news agency IRNA before his
departure, Yassin said that his talks with Iranian officials had
been "highly fruitful," adding that he had briefed Iranian
officials on the latest developments in Palestinian and Hamas'
stance on regional situation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the release of four Palestinian prisoners captured
by Iran during the Iran-Iraq war (1980-88) was an affirmative
response given by Iranian officials to his request.
</P>
<P>
Some Palestinians joined the Iraqis in their bloody fightings
with Iranians which left about 1 million people from both sides
dead or injured.
</P>
<P>
Yassin told reporters that support for the Palestinian nation
and its right to self-determination is quite obvious in the
position of the Iranian officials and people.
</P>
<P>
The paraplegic Hamas leader, who was released from Israeli jail
last October, arrived here on Tuesday after visiting Egypt, Syria
and Qatar. He is reportedly to visit Kuwait on the fifth leg of his
multi-nation tour in the region.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, he met Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei, President Mohammad Khatami, former President Hashemi
Rafsanjani and other senior Iranian officials, who reiterated
Iran's support for Palestinian resistance against Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Yassin has repeatedly pledged to continue struggle against
Israel until "the liberation of Palestine without ceding an inch
of Palestinian land." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
