<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Plans to Give Parents Child Sick Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain is planning to give parents
of sick children legal right to time off work to look after their
children under new laws which will come into force in the country
at the end of 1999, national newspapers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that under a European directive in the Social
Chapter, which the UK government signed up after last year's
general election, employers will have to grant time off for
parents of sick children.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that the move will be discussed with
employers as to how much time off should be given and whether or
not it will be paid.
</P>
<P>
At present, parents of sick children declare themselves sick
when they really need time off work to care for a sick child. Some
others take paid holiday to look after their sick children.
</P>
<P>
Harriet Harman, the Social Security Secretary, is reportedly
very keen to see such measures as part of the government's package
of "family friendly" employment policies, together with childcare,
the minimum wage and working family tax credits.
</P>
<P>
Harman said in a recent speech: "This package of measures is
crucial to making sure that mothers and fathers can take time out
to care for their children without jeopardising their employment
prospects". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
