<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Peace Talks Resume as Famine Spreads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
(by Xu Jianmei)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The warring sides in Sudan
restarted peace talks here Monday as famine continues to bite in
southern Sudan where civil war has dragged on since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Few are expecting a breakthrough from the talks, which is the
second round to be ended here Tuesday compared to the first one
which lasted for about two weeks late last year, a senior
Khartoum diplomat told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"The parties to the conflict have not reconsidered their
positions" since then, sighed Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya
Godana when opening the talks.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman heads a seven-member
delegation while Nhial Deng, the rebel governor of southern Bahr
el Ghazal Province, acts as the top negotiator for the rebel
Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) and its political wing
Sudan People's Liberation Movement (SPLM), Xinhua was told.
</P>
<P>
Their talks are under the auspices of the Inter-Government
Authority of Development (IGAD) which groups Kenya#,Uganda,
Eritrea, Ethiopia, Djibouti, Sudan and Somalia. The talks also
have a sideshow of an IGAD ministrial-level meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the last talks, "the two parties could not agree on
two issues, namely the right of self-determination for the people
of southern Sudan and the relationship between state and
religion," Godana noted.
</P>
<P>
"This stalemate led to the adjournment of the negotiations"
and brings about great pessimism on the prospect of the ongoing
talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
A report by special envoys mandated to shuttle between the
two sides when the last round of talks broke up in November "was
not encouraging," he lamented.
</P>
<P>
However, Godana called for "an urgent solution" to the
conflicts as southern Sudanese "have for long been faced with
famine due to the ravages of war."
</P>
<P>
Famine crisis in southern Sudan, especially in the Bahr el
Ghazal area, "has now reached catastrophy," said SPLM spokesman
John Luk Jok after the opening ceremony, urging for more
international humanitarian aid to the area.
</P>
<P>
"Hundreds and thousands of people (there) are starving to
death due to famine" caused by the protracted war and poor
weather last year, said Jok.
</P>
<P>
"The SPLM/A resolves to respect and observe free and
unhindered access of humanitarian relief assistance to the needy
people of our country and particularly in Bahr el Ghazal region
through the establishment of corridors of tranquillity," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Operation Lifeline of Sudan (OLS) said that it was
allowed Sunday by the Sudanese government to use four more
aircraft to fly aid to southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"With five C-130 aircraft and other modes of transport, OLS
will be able to deliver approximately 6,000 tos of food
assistance per month," said the OLS in a news release.
</P>
<P>
"This will greatly assist OLS to meet the food needs of
380,000 people in both government and rebel-held areas of Bahr el
Ghazal and an additional 410,000 people facing severe hunger in
other parts of southern Sudan," the OLS said.
</P>
<P>
Peace negotiations between Sudan's warring sides restarted at
the end of October last year after a three-year deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The war, broke out in 1983 between the Moslem-ruled Khartoum
government in the north and the SPLA fighting for more autonomy
and religious freedom in the animist and Christian-dominated
south.
</P>
<P>
So far more than 1.3 million Sudaneses have been killed by
the war and war-related famines. Another 365,000 have now been
forced to live on alien lands as refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
