<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-04 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait, Lebanon Agree to Exempt, Trim Customs Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and Lebanon have agreed
to exempt customs fees on a number of products in their bilateral
trade, an Lebanese trade official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Al-Amin, director general at the Lebanese Economy and
Trade Ministry, told the Kuwait News Agency after attending a
three-day meeting of the Kuwaiti-Lebanese Technical Trade
Committee here.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides have signed an accord under which customs
fees will be totally exempted on agricultural, animal and natural
products between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Some of the industrial products would also be free of customs
charges, while fees on the rest of the industrial products would
be reduced by 20 percent annually until they are fully exempted
from customs fees in years, he added without specifying.
</P>
<P>
He said this accord was signed to activate a 1996 trade
agreement between the two countries. It will be referred soon to
the concerned ministers of the two countries for final
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
