<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- No matter how much the participants insist that U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright meetings in London Monday
with leaders of Israel and Palestine, the events surrounding Vice
President Al Gore's Middle East swing have combined to make them
seem crucial to prospects for regional peace.
</P>
<P>
-- The shuttle Columbia glided to a sunny Florida touchdown
Sunday and crew members, still wobbly after 16 days of
weightlessness, were immediately subjected to a battery of tests,
while space-adapted lab rats were whisked away for quick
dissection.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Peace talks between the Islamic militants of the Taliban
and its opponents to resolve years of bitter and conflict in
Afghanistan broke down and were "suspended indefinitely," said
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
-- As the bad news on Japan's economy continues, the Japanese
are expressing contempt for Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto,
who started his term as one of the nation's most popular leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The EU moved closer to launching a common currency, as EU
leaders picked the new monetary union's 11 founding members and
set exchange rates. The weekend summit saw a bitter battle over
who should lead the new European Central Bank, underscoring the
challenges Europe faces.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton, seeing the Asian financial
crisis as the biggest threat to U.S. growth, signaled he would get
more directly involved in pressing Japan's prime minister to
stimulate and reform the economy despite enormous political
pressure against such action. 
</P>
