<HEADLINE> 65 Illegal Foreign Immigrants Captured in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Gendarme soldiers on Monday
captured 65 illegal foreign immigrants who crossed into Turkey in
the hope of fleeing to Europe, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said that the Turkish soldiers had taken into
custody the illegal immigrants from northern Iraq, Bangladesh and
Iran, who were travelling in a truck near Sazlikoy village in
Aydin province in western Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The illegal immigrants, who hired the truck, included five
women and three children. They were planning to sail to
neighboring Greece, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Turkish officials as saying that the
interrogations of the illegal immigrants are continuing at the
Soke Gendarmerie Office. The 65 people will later be deported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali S. Town Kismayu Declared Battle Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 4 (Xinhua)-- Militia officers of the Marehan
sub-clan fighting for the control of the port town of Kismayu,
500 km south of Mogadishu, Monday declared this southern town of
Kismayu as a battle zone.
</P>
<P>
They also issued a stern warning to the international aid
agencies and business communities against coming in and operating
in the town.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement read on the VHF radios seven km
outside Kismayu to reporters here in the Somali capital, the
Marehan militiamen and their battle wagons won't shoulder the
security guarantees of any international or local flights trying
to use the airport in the town.
</P>
<P>
The statement also warned against any damage to the business
or humanitarian ferries trying to bring supplies to the town.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Omar Jama Artan, the militia leader of the Marehan SNF
faction, said the statement will also apply to the international
or local aid workers inside the town, adding that the aid
agencies and their flights will be given a further notice as soon
as the situation changes.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kismayu said a commercial ferry that left
Mogadishu for Kismayu four days ago could not dock into the port
following the increased insecurity precipitated by armed clashes
that drew very close to the town Sunday. The ferry, Al-Mansor,
has reportedly passed on to the Kenyan port of Mombasa Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the mass refugees exodus to the relatively
safer areas south of Kismayu, the militia commanders of the
Marehan Somali National Front (SNF) faction called civilians in
the town to remain calm and stay in their houses, adding that
"the militiamen of General Morgan themselves will be forgiven if
they disarm and surrender to the SNF forces."
</P>
<P>
Colonel Artan also said he is going to his house inside
Kismayu town together with his fellow clan compatriots who were
ousted from the town last year. He also said his men won't kill
or take vengeance on anyone despite the current hostility between
the two sub-clans of Darod, Majerten and Marehan.
</P>
<P>
The Marehan militia commanders also warned against the
possible spread of the fighting to other regions where the two
sub-clans live together, including Somalia's central region of
Mudug.
</P>
<P>
They accused General Morgan of trying to instigate armed
clashes in the town of Galkayo among the supporters of the two
sides. Nearly 100 people have been killed and 200 others wounded
since the clashes began over 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kismayu was tense Monday with almost all its
people mobilized to defend the town against the Marehans. More
fighting for the control of the town is eminent in the next few
days as both sides continue their preparations to launch more
attacks. 
</P>
