<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Import 2 Million Tons of Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Southern African countries
will need to import more than two million tons of maize this
year, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two million tons would cover an estimated deficit of
between 2.18 million and 3.08 million tons of the staple food in
the region, SAPA quoted a regional food magazine as saying.
</P>
<P>
The magazine report, which covered 11 of the 14 members of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC), said maize
harvests were forecast at between 15.24 million and 16.14 million
tons this year, compared with last year's 17.05 million tons.
</P>
<P>
While production was forecast to increase in Angola, Malawi,
Mozambique, Swaziland and Zambia, where rainfall was normal to
above normal, Lesotho, South Africa and Zimbabwe were adversely
affected by delayed rains and dry spells in February.
</P>
<P>
Angola's maize output was forecast to rise by 10 percent from
last season's yield, but it still faced a maize shortfall of over
381,000 tons this marketing season, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Maize deficit in Zimbabwe would go up to 610,000 tons this
year, as the country's production was expected to decline by 35
percent to 1.42 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Only Mozambique and South Africa were projected to have maize
surplus.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's yield was set to rise to 1.2 million tons, which
means a surplus of 157,000 tons for 1998/99. South Africa was
expected to have a small domestic surplus of 112,000 tons as
maize output fell from nine million last year to 7.75 million.
</P>
<P>
The region was predicted to have a total cereal shortfall of
4.56 million tons in the 1998/99 marketing year, more than double
last year's shortfall of 1.83 million tons.
</P>
<P>
This would require an import of between 3.2 million and 4.56
million tons of cereal, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
