<HEADLINE> 3 S. African States Suffer Power Blackouts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe, Zambia and Botswana
experienced power blackouts Monday following a major fault on the
Bindura (Zimbabwe) - Cahora Bassa (Mozambique) line, the Zimbabwe
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Francis Masawi, transmission director of the Zimbabwe
electricity supply authority, said the loss of power was due to a
failure of Southern African Development Community (SADC)'s
inter-connected power system.
</P>
<P>
Zambia and Zimbabwe were the worst affected as they are in the
middle of the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe experienced a nationwide blackout for about five
hours from 10:17 am until services were restored around 14:30 pm.
</P>
<P>
There was another blackout around 15:30 pm following a line
fault on the South African Eskom-Matimba-Insukameni line with
services restored on an on-and-off basis.
</P>
<P>
Botswana experienced a blackout following Zimbabwe's failure
to transmit its imported power from South Africa during the
blackout.
</P>
<P>
"We are operating in an inter-connected power system and any
event on the network will affect all the power systems in the
SADC region, with Zambia and Zimbabwe being the worst affected as
they fall in the center of the system," Masawi said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe imports 300 and 400 megawatts from South Africa and
Mozambique respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
