<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-04 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Disappointed Over Failure of U.S. Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus expressed disappointment on
Monday over the failure of the latest United States efforts to
resume the intercommunal dialogue on the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government was "disappointed and displeased" that
the U.S. effort to revive the Cyprus peace talks aimed at forming
a bizonal and bicommunal federation has broken down, government
spokesman Christos Stylianides told reporters.
</P>
<P>
His comments came after U.S. presidential emissary Richard
Holbrooke ended his three-day shuttle mission here without
succeeding to get Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash back to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides blamed the Turkish Cypriot side for the lack of
progress, which he said was caused by its intransigence.
</P>
<P>
"The international community must understand that the Turkish
side is exclusively responsible for the lack of progress in
efforts to reach a comprehensive settlement of the Cyprus
question," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after a failed pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been trying to reunify the
island under the bizonal and bicommunal formula proposed by the
United Nations. But so far no tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides
has briefed Greek Cypriot political leaders on the outcome of
Holbrooke's visit, and the National Council will probably meet on
Friday to discuss the developments.
</P>
<P>
The council, which comprises leaders of Greek Cypriot political
parties, is the top advisory body to the president on handling the
protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference during the day at the end of
his visit, Holbrooke said that Denktash demanded his entity in
northern Cyprus be recognized and Cyprus suspend its accession
talks with the European Union before the peace talks can be
resumed.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that Denktash's preconditions "make progress
difficult."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by
Turkey, against the internationally recognized Republic of Cyprus
predominated by the Greek Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
