<HEADLINE> Kohl Defends EU Central Bank Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 4 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Monday
made a talk to defend a European Union compromise to split the
term of the first president of the European central bank (ECB)
between rival French-and German-back candidates, stressing that
the decision would not undermine the independence of the new bank.
</P>
<P>
While admitting that there had been a hard fight between
Germany and France on the ECB leadership issue, Kohl also stressed
in Bonn that the relations between the two countries had not been
marred for this reason.
</P>
<P>
"Friendship means that one can talk about everything with a
friend even when they have different views," Kohl argued at a news
conference on Monday.
</P>
<P>
After more than 10 hours of heated squabbling at their weekend
summit in Brussels, leaders of the 15 EU members decided to
appoint the former Dutch central bank chief Wim Duisenberg as the
first ECB president.
</P>
<P>
The decision, however, was followed by a statement from
Duisenberg, who is favored by most EU states except France, that
he would only serve half of his eight-year term in order to make
way for the French central bank governor Jean-Claude Trichet.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement has drawn widespread criticism in Germany with
the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) accusing Kohl of
caving in to French pressure on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"The rotten compromise of Brussels is a personal defeat for
Kohl," said SPD European policy spokeswoman Heidemarie
Wieczorek-Zeul.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, however, noted that the Dutchman had offered to retire
early under his own free will and due to his old age.
</P>
<P>
The German chancellor also denied speculations that Bonn and
Paris had agreed previously to install a Frenchman at the head of
the European central bank in return for locating the bank in
Frankfurt, Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
