<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC Rejects Smear Campaign Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling African
National Congress (ANC) Monday rejected again National Party
(NP)'s claims that the ANC is behind a smear campaign against NP
leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk.
</P>
<P>
ANC member of parliament Willie Hofmeyr Monday repeated a
statement made by the ANC last week that it was not involved in
any way in allegations that van Schalkwyk paid for homosexual
sex.
</P>
<P>
He said his party would not "stoop to such tactics" and would
seek a meeting with the NP leader to set the record straight.
</P>
<P>
A weekly newspaper reported Friday that van Schalkwyk was at
the center of a police probe, following allegations by a
convicted thief, David Hermanus, who is serving a prison
sentence, that the NP leader paid him 20 Rand (4 U.S. Dollars)
for sex in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report triggered immediate reaction from the NP, the
country's biggest opposition party, which claimed that the ANC
was the mastermind of the allegations aimed at smearing the NP
leader ahead of the 1999 general election.
</P>
<P>
The NP said Sunday that Hofmeyr was kept informed about the
development on the homosexual charges, and his subordinate had
regular telephone contact with Hermanus.
</P>
<P>
It also said a list of possible questions and answers relating
to Hermanus's allegations was found in his cell, creating the
impression of "a coaching document."
</P>
<P>
Hofmeyr said the NP claims showed it had resorted to the kind
of cheap smear tactics of which it claimed had been a victim.
</P>
<P>
ANC's national leaders had dealt with the matter with complete
integrity and had been entirely open about Hermanus' approach to
his office, Hofmeyr said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
