<HEADLINE> New Phone Lines Link Cyprus' Divided Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus inaugurated an automated
telephone system on Monday aimed at improving the communications
between the two divided communities of Greek Cypriots and Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration ceremony, visiting United States
presidential emissary Richard Holbrooke urged the two communities
to "use these lines to reach out to old friends they have not
talked to in many years."
</P>
<P>
"I believe firmly in communications. Communications break down
barriers. Let us not minimize the importance of today's step,"
Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy attended the ceremony hours before his departure
from here. He failed to talk Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash into returning to the
negotiating table during his three-day shuttle mission here.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Resident Representative for Cyprus Gustave
Feissel has said the new, automated system will increase the
annual handling capacity of telephone calls from 100,000 to more
than 750,000.
</P>
<P>
The system, at an estimated cost of 80,000 U.S. dollars, was
funded by the U.S. through Office of the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
For years, the U.N. has provided the only phone connection
between Turkish Cypriots in the north and Greek Cypriots in the
south on the Mediterranean island, through the switchboard of the
U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. says the existing system, which is manually operated,
has become overburdened because of increasing demand from the two
sides and it was unable to cope with it.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed pro-Athens coup by the Greek Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
