<HEADLINE> Kuwait Holds International Women's Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 4 (Xinhua) -- A three-day international
woman's conference on the "future perspective for the Kuwaiti
women in the society" started here on Monday to discuss ways of
boosting woman's role in Kuwait's economy.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Minister of Planning and Minister of State for
Administrative Development Affairs Ali Moussa Al-Moussa said in
the inaugural speech that woman's contribution to the Kuwaiti work
force and economy will double in the near future.
</P>
<P>
President of the Women Committee Haifaa Al Abd al-Jaber told
the conference that the women in Kuwait account for one third of
its work force.
</P>
<P>
He said that activating woman's role would be a way to
restructure the labor force and then the demographic makeup.
</P>
<P>
The conference organized by the Women Committee in the Social
Reform Society is attended by researchers from Kuwait, the United
States, Malaysia, Britain and Sweden and several international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Chairwoman of the committee Saud Al-Jarallah has said that the
conference will focus on bringing to Kuwait new ideas as "office
at home," a system she said would enable the women to have new
access to the labor market.
</P>
<P>
"This will open up opportunities for women to work from home in
about 46 occupations," she said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Jarallah said during last two years, over 4,300 working
women, including 1,600 university graduates, were forced to give
up jobs because of social commitments.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics have shown that only 60,000 out of more
than 147,000 Kuwaiti women who hold educational qualifications,
including over 23,000 university graduates, are working.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, there are over 87,000 educated women,
including 2,367 university graduates, are not working due to
domestic and social commitments.
</P>
<P>
Female population currently account for 50.4 percent of the
710,000 citizens in Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
