<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Reduce Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Five countries of the Common Market
for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) have reduced tariffs by
80 percent in line with the organization's goal of establishing a
free trade area by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
They are Zimbabwe, the Comoros, Kenya, Sudan and Uganda.
Meanwhile, Eritrea, Malawi and Mauritius have managed to reduce
their tariffs by 70 percent, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a report on regional integration, COMESA said all other
member countries except Angola, the Democratic Republic of Congo,
Ethiopia and Tanzania which have not reduced tariffs even by 60
percent and those which still enjoy a derogation from publishing
these tariffs, are deemed to have reduced by either 60 percent or
70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho, Swaziland and Namibia, which are also members of the
South African Customs Union, are mentioned in the report as
countries that enjoy lessening authority or law from publishing
the tariffs.
</P>
<P>
"The problems some countries face are that they are applying
tariff reduction rates to already low national rates, leading to
inequitable revenue losses and making exports to countries with
higher national rates less competitive," COMESA said.
</P>
<P>
"There is also a problem with application of the tariff
reduction program at different stages by different countries," it
said, adding: "These problems are seen as temporary, if the free
trade area is achieved by 2000, and by the principle of
reciprocity."
</P>
<P>
The COMESA treaty includes a standstill provision so that
intra-COMESA tariffs are reduced together, avoiding one country
raising tariffs after initial reduction.
</P>
<P>
COMESA was established in December 1994 to promote regional
integration through trade development, replacing the Preferential
Trade Area for Eastern and Southern Africa, which had been in
existence since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Its members are Angola, Burundi, the Comoros, the Democratic
Republic of Congo, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Rwanda, Seychelles, Sudan,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
