<HEADLINE> Baghdad Mourns for Young Victims of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 4 (Xinhua) -- A mass funeral of 52 Iraqi children
who died because of shortages of food and medicine resulting from
the sanctions imposed on Iraq was held here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The funeral procession, attended by hundreds of people
including Arab delegations attending the 5th Arab People's Forces
Conference, started from al-Rasheed street and headed for the
U.N. Development Program (UNDP) building in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Sultan al-Shawi, chairman of the Iraqi Children Society, said
in a statement that this new batch of innocent Iraqi children
represents the "martyrs of the unjust embargo," which is
maintained because of the positions adopted by the U.S. and
British governments.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said that the United States and Britain refused to
lift the sanctions even after Iraq has fulfilled its obligations
under the relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
These two governments should bear the responsibility for this
crime, he added, appealing to the international community to take
urgent actions to lift the sanctions and put an end to the
"genocide."
</P>
<P>
Family members and relatives of these dead children shouted
slogans condemning the "inhumane actions" taken by U.S. and
British governments' against the Iraqi people and children in
particular.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shawi, on behalf of dead children's families, delivered a
protest letter to the UNDP officials here.
</P>
<P>
Saad Khasim Hammoudi, secretary-general of the Arab People's
Forces Conference, delivered a message on behalf of the
participants urging U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to help
lift the sanctions immediately to put an end to the suffering of
the Iraqi Children.
</P>
<P>
More than 1 million Iraqi children have reportedly died due to
the acute shortage of food and medicine caused by the
U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
