<HEADLINE> Armenia Returns WWII Booty to Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Armenia Monday returned to Germany a
total of 575 pieces of German cultural treasures seized by the
former Soviet Union after World War II.
</P>
<P>
The returned treasures include valuable books, manucripts and
music records. Most of them had been removed shortly before the end
of the war from libraries in large German cities to avoid allied
air bombings and hidden in rural areas where they were seized by
Soviet troops after 1945.
</P>
<P>
Armenia is the second former Soviet republics to return war
booty to Germany after Georgia.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that this is a signal for other countries," said Kinkel
Monday in Bonn in a clear reference to Russia, which still holds
most of the so-called "booty art" seized from Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
Although Russian President Boris Yeltsin has agreed to return
the art works, the Russia parliament has so far asserted Moscow's
ownship.
</P>
<P>
Many Russians view the art as legitimate compensation for the
wartime suffering of the Soviet people and for the many Russian
treasures destroyed during the German invasion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
