<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-04 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Vice President Meets U.N. Chief's Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan on Monday met with Prakash Shah, U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's Special Envoy in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Ramadan mentioned the Iraqi leadership's
open letter to the U.N. Security Council early this month, and
reiterated the threat that if Iraq gets no positive response, its
relation with the Security Council will be harmed.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has demanded the Council to remove the nearly eight-year
old crippling sanctions in recognition of Iraq's compliance with
the relevant U.N. resolutions and its fulfillment of obligations.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council last week decided to keep the sanctions in
place, on the basis of the assessment of the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq that there has been
"virtually no progress" in verifying Baghdad's banned weapon-free
claims.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM chairman Richard Butler said Iraq failed to come up with
sound evidence to substantiate its claims that it has dismantled
all nuclear, chemical and biological weapons, as well as ballistic
missiles.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramadan told the special envoy that Iraq had exposed
the lies and allegations written in the half-yearly UNSCOM report
submitted by Butler to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The report is a political one instead of a technical one, and
reveals Butler's ill intentions, Ramadan said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq will continue to expose the anti-Iraq policy
pursued by the American and British governments and Butler, which
aims to maintain the embargo and continue aggressions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Shah praised Iraq's cooperation with the United
Nations, pointing out that many members in the Security Council
believe that progress has been made through the Iraqi cooperation
with UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy said the atmosphere now is to the advantage
of Iraq and more positive than several months ago.
</P>
<P>
During the latest Iraq-U.N. weapons inspection crisis, the
United States and Britain threatened military action to force Iraq
to open its presidential sites suspected of hiding prohibited
weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
Under the Annan-brokered agreement which defused the crisis in
February, a special group of senior U.N. diplomats and UNSCOM
inspectors visited all the eight presidential sites, but found no
banned weapons or materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
