<HEADLINE> French FM to Testify at Parliamentary Hearing on Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 4 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine
will testify on Tuesday at a public hearing of the information
commission of the French National Assembly on Rwanda, reported
Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine will be the first government minister in service to be
summoned by the information commission. He will answer questions
concerning the role played by France in Rwanda from 1990 to 1994,
during which time he served as secretary general of President
Francois Mitterrand.
</P>
<P>
In his book entitled ""the World of Francois Mitterrand,"
Vedrine said that it is ""false, absurd and disgraceful" to
accuse France of deliberately supporting" Rwandan President
Juvenal Habyarimana.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary commission will also summon on Wednesday
Admiral Jacques Lanxade, former chief of staff of the French armed
forces under President Mitterrand, at a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
Three other military personalities who participated in the
""Noroit" military operation staged by French troops from August
1988 to July 1991 in Rwanda will also testify at a separate
closed-door hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The commission earlier summoned former Prime Minister Edouard
Balladur and three former ministers in his government, as well as
the son of President Mitterrand Jean-Christophe Mitterrand who
served as advisor on African affairs of his father, for testifying
on the role played by France in Rwanda before and during the 1994
genocide against Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
All of them denied any involvement by France in the genocide,
in which about one million people were killed.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government accuses France of ""having Rwandan blood
on its hand." 
</P>
</TEXT>
