<HEADLINE> S. Africa Fails to Curb HIV/AIDS: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma
admitted Monday that her department had failed to curb the spread
of HIV/AIDS in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the department's budget vote in parliament in Cape
Town, Zuma said HIV/AIDS had become "a very serious problem which
was threatening to destroy the socio-economic fabric of the
country.
</P>
<P>
"We admit we have not been successful in curbing the spread of
HIV/AIDS," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Health Department said earlier it intended to make AIDS
disease and deaths notifiable by law this year.
</P>
<P>
This would ensure that the necessary information could be
collected for planning and the provision of adequate services,
the department said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to successes of the Health Department, Zuma said the
dire shortage of doctors, especially in rural areas, had been
alleviated through government-to-government agreements, while a
permanent solution was being sought with the introduction of
community service for young doctors as from July this year.
</P>
<P>
The South African government headed by President Nelson
Mandela has promised to make health care accessible to all those
South Africans who had disabilities.
</P>
<P>
Of the 35,000 wheelchairs needed by 1997, 28,530 had been
delivered. Of the 800 hearing aids needed for 1997, the
government had delivered 732, the department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
