<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes Further OPEC Production Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Monday expressed welcome to
further oil production cuts by members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) in order to shore up oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
"Iran welcomes any further production cuts by the OPEC members
to stabilize the oil market," Ali Akbar Gharni, an official from
the National Iranian Oil Company (NIOC) in charge of the OPEC
affairs, was quoted by the official news agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gharni said that cooperation among the OPEC member states to
honor the production quotas will help stabilize the oil prices,
adding that Iran is abiding by its quota reduction fixed by OPEC
in March.
</P>
<P>
In order to strengthen oil prices, the OPEC ministerial
meeting decided to cut a total of 1.245 million barrels per day
(bpd) while Iran promised to cut its crude output by 140,000 bdp.
</P>
<P>
"After OPEC announcement on production cut, the oil prices
rose by two dollars per barrel" to reach 13 dollars, he said,
predicting that the price for OPEC crude basket will maintain
13-14 dollars per barrel this year.
</P>
<P>
The NIOC director of international affairs and crude marketing
Hojjatollah Ghanimifard confirmed on Saturday that Iran has cut
oil output by 140,000 bpd from April 1 according to the OPEC
decision.
</P>
<P>
As the world's third largest oil exporter after Saudi Arabia
and Norway, Iran relies on petrodollars for around 80 percent of
its hard currency earnings and up to 40 percent of government
revenues on a production quota of 3.6 million bpd in 1997 and 3.94
million bpd in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, oil prices plunged to the lowest point in more
than nine years, inflicting a serious blow to Iran's ailing
economy.
</P>
<P>
Expecting more badly-needed petrodollars, Iran hopes the OPEC
members agree on a new round of production reduction in the June
meeting in Vienna when it will decide on the production quotas for
the next six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
