<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Chiefs of Defense Staff Meet on S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The chiefs of defense staff from west
African countries began to draw a plan Monday to consolidate
security in war-ravaged Sierra Leone after the successful
reinstatement of the elected government to power.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, held in the Ghanaian capital Accra, is
expected to enable the chiefs of defense staff to make
recommendations to their heads of state on the future role of the
sub-regional peace-keeping force ECOMOG in securing a durable
peace in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Some of the issues that should be addressed at the meeting,
according to Ghana's foreign minister, include the objectives
insisted to achieve the role of ECOMOG, the rules of engagement,
the strength of the force required and the resources needed for
the task.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Timothy Shelpidi of
Nigeria said in addition to 10,000 troops already on the ground,
at least 6,000 soldiers and logistics are required to commission
the job.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional force dislodged the military junta in
mid-February which paved the way for the return of Sierra Leone's
legitimate government, ousted in a coup last May, from exile in
neighboring Guinea in March.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is now carrying out a final campaign to mop up the
remnants of the junta and allied rebels in eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The force earlier completed its peace keeping mission in
Liberia, ensuring a successful election of the post-war
government of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the security situation in both countries may still
have an impact particularly on the fragile economy of west
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the pledge of the international community to
assist the restoration of democracy in Sierra Leone, The United
Nations appealed in March for a three-month emergency support of
11 million U.S. Dollars for Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
However, U.N. Special Envoy to Sierra Leone Francis Okello
disclosed at the meeting Monday morning that only 1.9 million
Dollars had been in place so far.
</P>
<P>
It was one thing to restore the government and quite another
to consolidate the peace, he said, quoted by a British
Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
But the Ghanaian minister added that he was confident that the
donor countries would not let Sierra Leoneans down.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by representatives of only seven out
of the 16 member countries of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS), according to the report.
</P>
<P>
However, a delegate was quoted as saying that this did not
necessarily translate into apathy on the part of the countries
that were absent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
