<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Moves for W. Central African Shipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has initiated
moves to establish a coastal shipping company in the west and
central African sub-region in a bid to boost trade in this area.
</P>
<P>
So far the preliminary stage for the setting up of the company
has been completed, according to Transport Minister Maj.-Gen.
Ibrahim Gumel.
</P>
<P>
"Government has created the enabling framework for the company
to be established and has equally sensitized the nations in the
sub-region on the need for the company," Gumel said here over the
weekend, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria Monday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Nigerian government is committed to the
objectives of trade liberalization and economic integration,
particularly as it affects the west and central African
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
"But for our country to benefit from the gains of economic
integration, we must have our own facilities to service the trade
in the sub-region," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said Nigeria must position itself to take advantage of the
large volume of consignments that pass through its territorial
waters as trans-shipment cargos.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, the government has begun to review the
national shipping policy.
</P>
<P>
"In so doing, government is not loosing sight of the need to
harmonize all national shipping policies within a broad policy
for the west and central African sub-region."
</P>
<P>
Gumel also urged a strong presence of relevant enforcement
agencies for a round-the-clock surveillance at the sea ports of
Nigeria to keep them perfectly safe for ships, cargos and lives.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the major threats to maritime trade
in Nigeria include piracy, smuggling and pilfering, as well as
pollution of the sea and channels, and more recently drug
trafficking and toxic waste dumping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
