<HEADLINE> Israel Positive in Trade Talks with Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli officials Monday sent positive
signals to Jordan's demands for expanding exports to the
Palestinian self-rule areas and enlarging a Jordanian-Israeli
industrial zone, Jordan's official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordan stressed the importance of putting more Jordanian goods
on the A1 and A2 lists between the Palestinians and the Israelis,
which allow duty-free exports to the Palestinian markets,
Jordanian Minister of Trade, Commerce and Supply Hani Mulqi said.
</P>
<P>
Among the Jordanian products destined for the Palestinian
markets through the two lists include cement, fruits, vegetables
and minerals, Mulqi said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side responded positively to the request, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mulqi held talks with his Israeli counterpart Natan Sharansky
on bilateral trade during the day in Petra, a town about 240
kilometers south of Amman.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Jordanian side also asked to expand the
Qualified Industrial Zone (QIZ) in Irbid, some 80 kilometers north
of the Jordanian capital, whose products can be exported to the
United States duty-free.
</P>
<P>
"The Jordanian side expressed the willingness to extend the
QIZ to other areas in the future so that there will be more
factories to be established in the kingdom to benefit from
privileges given to the QIZ," Mulqi said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials have also expressed readiness to accept the
demand, he added.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Jordan and Israel agreed on the need to put technical
standards and specifications on the companies in the QIZ, so that
their products can be really qualified for the duty-free
treatment, according to the Jordanian minister.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's exports to the Palestinian self-rule areas reached 12
million U.S. dollars in 1997 and its imports stood at 22.9 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accused Israel of trying maintain
monopoly of the Palestinian markets, as only 5 percent of the
Palestinian imports have come from countries other than Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
