<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Trafficking Increases in Africa: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 4 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations agency has
found that Africa is likely to emerge as a key transit region for
traffickers of drugs such as cocaine and heroin.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. International Drug Control Program (UNDCP) cited weak
law enforcement structures, acute economic, political and social
problems and the strengthening of legal controls in other parts of
the world as the reasons for the situation.
</P>
<P>
In its note to correspondents here on Monday, the UNDCP said it
will enlighten the press on the situation at a briefing on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Already South Africa, Kenya and some West-African countries
are being used by international trafficking syndicates," the UNDCP
said.
</P>
<P>
It said: "resource and technical constraints make it difficult
for law enforcement agencies to take effective action against
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
"Leakage from drug trafficking through sub-Saharan Africa into
local communities and major cities is exacerbating the social
problems associated with poverty, political and tribal conflicts
and the spread of HIV/AIDS infection."
</P>
<P>
The briefing serves as a lead-up event to the Special Session
of the General Assembly on Drugs, which will take place in New
York from June 8-10.
</P>
<P>
Thirty heads of state and government have confirmed their
attendance with more expected, according to UNDCP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
