<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-04 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Critical of U.S. Envoy's Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
Monday expressed disappointment with remarks of United States
presidential envoy for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made a statement that Holbrooke has misinterpreted his
position on the intercommunal talks, stressing that he has never
ceased to represent the Republic of Cyprus, which is recognized
internationally.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before leaving here after a failed,
three-day mediation mission, Holbrooke said that "no one can
dispute that Glafcos Clerides does not represent or has control
over the people of northern Cyprus. He does not deny that, that is
a fact."
</P>
<P>
Clerides' statement underlined that "the President of the
Republic has never accepted that the relevant article of the 1960
Constitution, which specifies that he represents the Republic of
Cyprus, has ceased to be valid."
</P>
<P>
Clerides "regrets that it was not possible during the
consulations with Mr. Holbrooke for progress to be made in the
process for a solution to the Cyprus problem," the statement read.
</P>
<P>
It added that the Turkish Cypriots insisted on "unreasonable
demands," namely the recognition of the Turkish entity in northern
Cyprus, the withdrawal of the application of Cyprus for European
Union membership and the lifting of trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
During his shuttle diplomacy, Holbrooke tried but failed to get
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash back to
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' peace process came to a standstill last summer when
Denktash, angered by European Union's decision to open accession
negotiations with Cyprus, walked out of talks with Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since Turkey landed its troops and
took over the northern third after a failed coup by Greek Cypriots
seeking union with Greece in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
