<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-04 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots Insist on Two States on Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash said on Monday that his followers will not give up
their principle of two states in Cyprus, according to a
report reaching here from Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Following his talks with U.S. president's Special Envoy
Richard Holbrooke on the divided island, Denktash told reporters
that the reason why no progress was reached concerning the Cyprus
issue during the visit of Holbrooke is the refusal of Greek
Cypriot side to recognize the Turkish Cypriot entity.
</P>
<P>
Denktash stressed that Holbrooke showed to the Greek Cypriot
side that the U.S. can not persuade the Turkish Cypriot side to
accept the views of the Greek Cypriots by force.
</P>
<P>
"We could not make the world recognize our sovereignty for 24
years, but we will not give up our principle of two states on the
island", said the Turkish Cypriot leader.
</P>
<P>
He said that the refusal to recognize the Turkish Cypriot
people as a community and treating them as second class citizens
are mistakes which will impede the solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Denktash stressed that he will not participate in any kind of
negotiation which aims to bargain the sovereignty of the Turkish
Cypriots with the S-300 missiles scheduled to be deployed on the
divided island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after a failed pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been trying to reunify the
island under the bizonal and bicommunal formula proposed by the
United Nations. But so far no tangible results have been
achieved.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on the same day at the
end of his visit, Holbrooke said that Denktash demanded his
entity in northern Cyprus be recognized and Cyprus suspend its
accession talks with the European Union before the peace talks
can be resumed.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke ended his three-day shuttle mission in Nicosia
without succeeding to get Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and
Denktash back to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared the breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which is only
reconized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
