<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Director-General Hopes to See China's Early Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Director-General of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) Renato Ruggiero said here on Monday that he and
the WTO members hoped that China would join the WTO as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody in the WTO believes that we need to have China in
the WTO because without China we will not have a world system,"
Ruggiero said when answering a question by Xinhua. "So it is
absolutely necessary to have China in the WTO."
</P>
<P>
"I do believe that it is in the interest of China to be in the
WTO as soon as possible in order that China can participate to the
improvement of the trading system for the 21st century," the WTO
director-general said.
</P>
<P>
However, Ruggiero said that China and those wishing to join the
WTO should also agree to abide by the rules and disciplines of the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
"We are making progress with China," Ruggiero said. "As for
when China will join the WTO, we really mean as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
But he declined to give a date or timetable for China's WTO
accession.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier interview, Ruggiero said that he hoped that China
would participate, as a full member of the WTO, in new round of
negotiations on services starting in 2000 according to the WTO
built-in agenda.
</P>
<P>
Besides China, there are 30 others negotiating their accession
to the 132-member WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
