<HEADLINE> UAE Banks Dollars in Lebanon to Support Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri
on Monday announced that the United Arab Emirates (UAE) has agreed
to deposit 100 million U.S. dollars in Lebanon's central bank to
support the country's currency.
</P>
<P>
Hariri made the announcement at the end of the weekly cabinet
session. He added that the loan, which carries a low interest rate
for a period of three years, will be transferred to the Bank of
Lebanon on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the loan was signed in UAE Monday by Lebanon's
central bank governor Riyad Salama and the representative of the
president of Abu Dhabi National Bank Mohammed Hablush, reported
Lebanon's National News Agency.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Salama as saying that the agreement shows
international confidence in Lebanon's currency and the future of
its economy at large.
</P>
<P>
The loan is the third one in less than a year with the same
purpose of shoring up the Lebanese pound. Saudi Arabia granted
Lebanon 600 million U.S. dollars at the end of last year and
Kuwait, 250 million dollars early this year.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese currency is under heavy devaluation pressure due
to the difficult economy and political uncertainty in anticipation
of the late-May local elections, the first in 35 years, and the
presidential election in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
