<HEADLINE> Greece Welcomes EU Statements on Greek Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday welcomed the European
Union's statements on the economic progress Greece has made in the
past months, saying that such statements were "a recognition of
the effectiveness of Athens' policies and encouragement for the
Greek government to continue its efforts towards the entry into
the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
In a weekend statement issued in Brussels, the EU finance
ministers expressed their satisfaction over the determination of
the Greek government to implement its policy on fiscal
restructuring and structural adjustment to enable Greece to
participate in the European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) in
January 2001.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said that the Greek
government was confident that it would meet the Maastricht
criteria in 2001 as ensuring social cohesion and unity.
</P>
<P>
Greece would submit a revised two-year economic convergence
plan to the EU by the end of May ahead of the planned adoption of
the euro in 2001, he added.
</P>
<P>
The new plan to align with other EU economies would carry an
extension to 2000 and take into account a devaluation of the Greek
drachma by 14 percent on March 14 that based entry into the
exchange rate mechanism (ERM).
</P>
<P>
Of the 15 EU members, Greece is now the only country which will
not join the EMU in January 1999 because it has failed to meet the
convergence criteria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
