<HEADLINE> Arab Leaders Expecting Breakthrough From London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 4 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan, Saudi Arabian
King Fahd Ibn Abdul Aziz and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on
Monday expressed hope that the Palestinian and Israeli leaders
will come out of the London meeting with a breakthrough in the
stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
In his separate telephone calls to Fahd and Mubarak, Hussein
hoped that the London meeting will be successful and the peace
process see some new lights, particularly on the
Palestinian-Israeli track.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu are now in London meeting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright separately to find a way out for the impasse of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Fahd echoed the king's hope that the meeting should achieve
tangible progress for the peace process on the Palestinian-Israeli
track and a just, comprehensive peace be reached in the region,
Jordan's official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak on his side also responded positively saying that the
meeting should help avoid any setback or diversion that might
befall the peace march and push it astray from its right course.
</P>
<P>
All the three leaders expressed their satisfaction with and
support for the Palestinians' positive response to a proposal put
forward by the United States to Israel to evacuate from some 13
percent of the occupied Palestinian land in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has reportedly accepted the proposal, while Netanyahu
rejected it, insisting that Israel can evacuate from no more
than 9 percent of the land.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deadlocked since
last March due to the expansion of Jewish settlements in Arab
East Jerusalem and other Israeli hardline policies. 
</P>
