<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Officials Urged to Beware of HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials of the
Zanzibar government have been challenged to enhance awareness of
the hazard of HIV/AIDS and ensure that the scourge does not
necessarily drain meager financial resources of the isles.
</P>
<P>
The challenge was delivered Monday by the chief minister,
Mohammed Bilal, when opening a five-day workshop on HIV/AIDS and
socio-economic development in the isles, according to a report
reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"For us in Africa, AIDS is always around the corner and the
majority of people who are infected do not know that they have
contracted the deadly disease," Dr Bilal told senior government
officials at the Breeze Beach Club.
</P>
<P>
"This is true for Zanzibar," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bilal said it is disheartening to note that the epidemic has
produced devastating effects in Africa, where people have the
lowest per capita income in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said it is necessary to sensitize the people to the hazard
of AIDS and make them know how it is so easy and unexpecting to
contract HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The seminar has been organized by the Zanzibar AIDS control
program and is being funded by the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The objective of the workshop is to create awareness among and
impart the basic knowledge to officials at the Zanzibar
government on the varied dimensions and implications of HIV/AIDS
and its impact on social development.
</P>
<P>
Similar workshops involving senior officials have already been
conducted in various sub-Saharan African countries including
Malawi, Zambia and Burkina Faso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
