<HEADLINE> U.S., Kuwait to Work on Iraqi War Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Kuwait are
to cooperate to investigate war crimes committed by Iraq during
its occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Visiting U.S. ambassador at large for war crime issues David
Scheffer said here on Monday that he has discussed with Kuwaiti
officials the documentation of crimes committed by Iraq during its
occupation of Kuwait from August 1990 to February 1991, Kuwait
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He applauded the research and documentation in this regard
carried out by the Kuwaiti authorities, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Scheffer said that he would work closely with Kuwaiti officials
in putting together a documentary record of Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein's regime in the respect of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
"I have spent a lot of time on the issue of Iraq and the record
of Saddam Hussein's regime and that record is a long one," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador said that his country is striving for the
establishment of an international criminal court to try war
criminals.
</P>
<P>
Scheffer, who is on a three-day visit, said that a five-week
conference is due to be held this summer in Italy in a bid to
draft a treaty for establishing the court.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. is determined that such a court be formed by
the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Scheffer is U.S. first ambassador at large for war crime
issues. He is charged with U.S. efforts to coordinate support for
the operation of Yugoslav and Rwanda war crimes tribunals. 
</P>
