<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Destroys Beijing's Largest Furniture Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A major fire engulfed the Yuquanying
Furniture Center, the largest furniture market in Beijing, at
around 17:30 (Beijing time) today and totally destroyed the
complex.
</P>
<P>
The center complex, covering 17,000 sq.m., is located in the
southwestern Fengtai District some 10 km from Tian'anmen Square.
</P>
<P>
The major portion of the structure was destroyed and most
furniture sustained heavy damage. "Combustible materials used to
construct the market halls fueled the blaze," according to a
fire-fighter.
</P>
<P>
Local fire departments responded to the fire immediately after
receiving reports at around 18:00. Some 70 emergency vehicles
went to the scene and fire-fighters extinguished the inferno
shortly before 7:00 this evening.
</P>
<P>
Heavy black smoke could be seen from Tian'anmen Square in the
center of the Chinese Capital. Fire-fighters prevented the blaze
from spreading water to surrounding buildings.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 onlookers and automobiles blocked access to
the area and law enforcement personnel prevented curious
onlookers, reporters and insurance inspectors from entering into
the site.
</P>
<P>
No casualties have been reported, according to a Fengtai
official. The fire was brought under control and officials from
concerned departments are currently investigating the cause.
</P>
<P>
The local public security bureau confirmed the blaze, but
refused to disclose further details.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the Beijing Fengtai Hospital were not called to the
scene. However, large numbers of fire-fighters, law enforcement
personnel and government officials immediately responded to the
scene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
