<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Farmers Disappointed by EU Ruling on Beef Export Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain's National Farmers Union
(NFU) expressed its disappointment on Tuesday over a European
Court of Justice ruling to maintain the ban on British beef
exports.
</P>
<P>
NFU president Ben Gill said in a statement that the farmers
were disappointed by the EU ruling and would continue their
efforts to get the ban lifted.
</P>
<P>
"The UK now has the toughest anti-BSE controls anywhere in the
world - it is only a matter of time before Europe must lift this
ban," Gill said.
</P>
<P>
He said the NFU was confident that the great progress now being
made meant the lifting of the ban was in sight.
</P>
<P>
The European Court of Justice on Tuesday upheld the European
Commission's right to ban British beef exports in March 1996 over
mad cow disease (BSE), ruling against Britain which challenged the
decision's validity.
</P>
<P>
There were two separate but related cases against the
Commission brought by the British government and others including
the UK's National Farmers Union, which has argued the ban did
irreparable damage to the country's livestock industry.
</P>
<P>
The European Union banned the British beef export in March 1996
after the British government admitted a possible link between mad
cow disease or BSE and a new variant of the human brain-wasting
condition Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
