<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Agrees to Republican Deal on Judges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton has agreed to nominate a conservative judge selected by a
Republican Senator to a federal appeals court in exchange for the
confirmation of one of his nominees, the New York Times reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will nominate Barbara Durham, the chief judge of the
Washington state Supreme Court, to the ninth U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, the Times quoted unidentified sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
In return, Senate Republicans will no longer stall William
Fletcher's appointment to the same appeals panel.
</P>
<P>
Fletcher, 52, a friend of Clinton who teaches law at the
University of California at Berkeley, has been waiting for the
appointment for more than three years.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans also agreed to stop blocking confirmation of
other Clinton nominees, the Times reported.
</P>
<P>
Presidents have traditionally handled nominees to federal
appeals courts.
</P>
<P>
Senate and administration sources told the Times the deal was
made to a large extent with Senator Slade Gorton, a Republican who
insisted that the president nominate Durham.
</P>
<P>
Some Washington state newspapers have called Durham, 55, the
most conservative judge on the state's high court.
</P>
<P>
The ninth Circuit is the largest of 13 regional courts which
are just below the U.S. Supreme Court. It covers nine western
states and two territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
