<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Bridge Opens in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A bridge linking the urban areas
of Hong Kong and Kowloon to the Western "New Territories" and the
Lantau Island, where the new airport is located, opened
Tuesday and will be put to use Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony Tuesday evening, Leung
Kwok-sun, director of highways of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, said that Ting Kau Bridge has advanced the
design and construction techniques of major cable-stayed bridges.
</P>
<P>
The bridge has introduced for the first time the economy
of a single pylon stem braced with cables like a ship's mast.
</P>
<P>
There are altogether three such pylons, being a rare double
main span cable-stayed bridge. The separate main decks are
suspended on both sides of the three bridge pylons.
</P>
<P>
Each deck carries three traffic lanes and a hard shoulder. With
main spans of 448 meters and 475 meters, and a total cable
supported length of 1,177 meters, the Ting Kau Bridge ranks among
the longest cable-stayed bridges in the world.
</P>
<P>
The project cost 1.73 billion HK dollars (222 million U.S.
dollars) and took 44 months to complete.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Ng, secretary for transport, said that the completion
of the Ting Kau Bridge clearly demonstrates the government's firm
commitment to providing a comprehensive transport infrastructural
network that will sustain and further improve economic
development, land use and hosing development in Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
