<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Addresses Reform of Grain Marketing System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Delegates agreed that the high growth rate for the national
economy accompanied by low inflation and successive good grain
harvests, an abundant market supply and basically stable prices
have created a good macro-environment for deepening reform.
</P>
<P>
The government has also gained experience in efficiently
regulating the grain market.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji urged concerned government departments to
refrain from directly interfering in the market activities of
grain companies, and noted that state-owned grain firms must
compete on the market and halt the practice of administrative
roles.
</P>
<P>
The central government will concentrate on the macro-control of
the national grain supply, while local governments will be
responsible for regional grain production and circulation, said
Zhu.
</P>
<P>
Grain reserves by the central government must be
separated from local grain reserves, and efforts must be
made to accelerate improvements in both central and local grain
reserve systems, according to the premier
</P>
<P>
"Under normal conditions, grain prices will be mainly set
by market supply and demand," said Zhu, adding that grain
companies should sell grain at market prices.
</P>
<P>
Zhu stressed that state-owned grain companies must play their
role as the main channel of grain marketing, and noted that
private firms will be strictly prohibited from directly purchasing
grain from rural markets.
</P>
<P>
He termed restructuring of the grain marketing system as one of
the central government's major reform measures for this year, and
pointed to it as a major task for the year's economic work.
</P>
<P>
The policy for purchasing excessive grain products from farmers
must be followed to the letter in order to ensure farmers maintain
their initiative for growing grain, said Zhu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Down as IMF Spooks Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market closed
lower Tuesday as investors reacted cautiously to the International
Monetary Fund's (IMF) call on the United States to alter interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index dropped 8.8 points, or 0.31 percent,
to 2803.5, off its high of 2814.1.
</P>
<P>
Senior dealer Peter Struk of Reynolds &AMP; Co. said the IMF's
announcement had "without a doubt" impacted on the equities
market. "That's why the futures started coming off," he said.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said that the U.S.
Federal Reserve must soon move to alter interest rates, with the
markets interpreting his comments as meaning higher rates.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of monetary policy it's always better to move earlier
than later," Camdessus told a Melbourne conference.
</P>
<P>
The third largest stock on market capitalization, BHP, fell 25
cents, or 1.69 percent, to 14.52 Australian dollars, with 4.71
million shares exchanged.
</P>
<P>
Funds manager AUSBIL Partners equities director Paul Xiradis
said that increasing concern that future bulk commodity sales of
iron ore and coal to Japan could be jeopardized by the weak
Japanese economy was weighing on the stock market, Xiradis said.
</P>
<P>
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. gained ground after a marginal rise
in its American Depository Receipts in the U.S. overnight, with
its ordinary shares gaining eight cents to 10.83 Australian
dollars and its preferred shares gaining five cents to 9.30.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished down 9.4 points at 1199.4 and
the all industrials index ended down 9.3 points at 4812.6.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a thin 265.31 million shares valued at
733.03 million Australian dollars (469.13 million U.S. Dollars).
Falls outnumbered rises 599 to 417, with 423 stocks closing
steady.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was the only major bank to gain ground,
closing up 5.6 cents, ANZ Banking Group dropped 10.7, Westpac
Banking Corp. fell 15 and Commonwealth Bank of Australia dipped
0.6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
