<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Says Indonesian President's Visit Momentous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's ambassador to Indonesia said
Tuesday the visit of Indonesian President Suharto to Cairo next
week will give a momentous push to bilateral relations for many
years to come.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egypt's Middle East News Agency (MENA),
Mohamoud Othman, said the timing of the visit added to its
significance as it coincides with the eighth G-15 Summit to be
held here next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit, to be attended by heads of state or the
government of developing countries from Latin America, Africa and
Asia, will review world economic developments, particularly the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Suharto will discuss with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak issues tabled on the summit's agenda such
as South-South cooperation in addition to the longstanding
bilateral relationship, according to MENA.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first Mubarak-Suharto tete-a-tete summit in 15
years, although both of them have met at larger regional or
international conferences, said the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
Suharto's visit to Egypt, which will begin Monday, will also
afford a great chance to discuss the ongoing financial crisis in
Southeast Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that this visit comes at a time Indonesia is
trying to recover from the shocks of the regional economic crisis,
the ambassador expressed belief that it will mark progress in
activating bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesians can benefit from Egypt's experience with the
International Monetary Fund in economic reform, Othman said,
voicing hope that bilateral talks would narrow the gap in their
trade balance that sharply tilts to Indonesia's favor.
</P>
<P>
Three agreements will be signed between the two countries on
avoiding double taxation, cooperation between central banks and
maritime transportation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was the first country to recognize Indonesia 50 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 was founded in 1989 as an offshoot of the Non-Aligned
Movement.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 members represent the emerging economies of the Third
World. They have 30 percent of the world's population and 27
percent of the Third World land area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
