<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisian Minister of Economic Development Taoufik
Baccar has said that the country has privatized 93 state-owned
companies from 1987 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
The move has resulted in 400 million dinars (about 336 million
U.S. dollars) of funds and a 50 percent rise of the transaction
volume of the companies, he added.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Chairman of the Saudi Ladaleider Shop Center Company
Abdel Aziz Fahd Al-Kridis has said that Saudi Arabia has invested
15 billion rials (4 billion dollars) in training work force.
</P>
<P>
Most of the money was used for training courses in English,
individual skills, business administration and marketing.
</P>
<P>
He said the investments in training have been aimed at
promoting employment of more national work force instead of
foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Treasury announced on Monday that it
would start accepting tenders for treasury bonds of 800 million
Egyptian pounds (235.3 million dollars) over a period of 91 days.
</P>
<P>
The treasury bonds offered for subscription last month yields
an average profit of 8.817 percent.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwait Stock Exchange announced on Monday
that it would carry out experimental dealing of futures.
</P>
<P>
The stock exchange would let one company do the dealings for a
period of six months before others are allowed to follow suit.
</P>
