<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environment Network Formed for Accession Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Tuesday
officially launched its environment network for the 11 countries
that are seeking union membership.
</P>
<P>
The network, known as AC-IMPEL, comprises officials from the
accession countries who deal with the implementation and
enforcement of environmental legislation.
</P>
<P>
The 11 accession countries are Hungary, Poland, the Czech
Republic, Estonia, Slovenia, Cyprus, Romania, Bulgaria, Slovakia,
Latvia and Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
European Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard, in charge of
environmental affairs, said: "The idea behind this network is a
simple and practical one. It is based on the recognition that
environmental law, which isn't implemented, is not worth the paper
it is printed on."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner stressed that both the 15-nation EU and the
accession countries had held enough talks on the environment and
it was time for genuine action.
</P>
<P>
"Action which addresses the real problems and difficulties for
the environment and does something about them. Action to control
industrial, urban and agricultural practices with an impact on the
environment.
</P>
<P>
Action to monitor the quality of the air, water and soil, and
action to improve the situation where it is found not to be
acceptable," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
