<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Trekking Lower on Bearish Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar shed more
than half a U.S. cent Tuesday and is expected to trek lower as
Australia's dismal trade performance continues to fuel sales of
the currency both offshore and at home.
</P>
<P>
Unfounded rumors that international ratings agency Standard &AMP;
Poor's could move to downgrade Australia's debt rating helped
drive the Australian dollar to a four month-low of 64.07 U.S.
cents Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The currency finished the local session at 64.14 U.S. cents,
from 64.65 at Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the trade figures had put Australia's exposure to
the Asian financial crisis in the spotlight in offshore markets.
</P>
<P>
"This whole Asian region is going to continue to be under the
microscope, and the prospects don't look that good for Aussie in
the short term," said Macquarie Bank associate director of foreign
exchange Brent Aggar.
</P>
<P>
"I think the sentiment is still bearish on the Aussie dollar
and I think we can expect to see it lower," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics Monday reported that the
trade deficit had blown out to a record 1.33 billion Australian
dollars (851.2 million U.S. dollars) in March, from 462 million
Australian dollars (295.6 million U.S. dollars) in February.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar closed at 85.37 from
86.08 against Japanese yen, and at 1.1431 from 1.1521 against
Deutsche marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
