<HEADLINE> UNITA's Massing of Troops Threatens Stability in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Massing of troops by the former
Angolan rebel National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) has posed great threat to the stability in the central
areas of the country, Mayor of Caala City, Paulino Maquina told
media Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Maquina said that the buildup of UNITA troops to the
south of Caala City of Huambo Province has enormously endangered
the stable situation there, both militarily and politically.
</P>
<P>
The looming-up of UNITA buildup is "extremely worrisome," the
mayor said, adding that safety of people's lives and their
properties is in great danger.
</P>
<P>
The rebels ambushed the vehicles running between Caala City
and other cities. And livestocks which is urgently needed in
farming are the hot target of robberies.
</P>
<P>
Police said that the remnants of UNITA troops launched attacks
in the suburb of Caala last Friday, killing three clan leaders
and forcing many villagers to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA remnants took Kuale Town in Malanje Province Sunday,
the Angolan News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the operation, the mayor of the town and two national
policemen were missing, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The police commander responsible for Malanje Province held
that they had been kidnaped by the UNITA troops.
</P>
<P>
This has been the second time that UNITA troops occupied Kuale
since the local government was reestablished early this year in
the town.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA troops blew up Lucala Bridge near the town in a bid
to resist the counterattack of the Angolan government army, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
Disturbing situation has lasted for quite a long time in the
central Angola. Both the Angolan government and the
United Nations observer missions have repeatedly stressed that
measures should be taken to crack down on the organized
criminals, and armed patroling has since been strengthened in the
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
