<HEADLINE> New Russian Government Nearly Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia's new cabinet, with just two
or three posts still to be filled, has been granted more power and
independence from President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who met Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko Tuesday to
decide on the last appointments, promised that Russia's new
government apparatus would be half the size of the outgoing one,
said Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also said he had granted the new government more power
by issuing a decree.
</P>
<P>
"Everything has been going through presidential structures. We
believed that this order was better, but it has proved bad," he
said.
</P>
<P>
That system had been "abolished", he said.
</P>
<P>
A basic agreement on relations between the presidential
agencies and the government had been signed earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under new rules, Yeltsin said Premier Sergei Kiriyenko "will
simply sign documents and the Cabinet will be responsible for
their implementation".
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also discussed with Kiriyenko "current issues" such as
wages, the funding of the army and the procedure of funding all
state organs.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday was the third time Yeltsin and Kiriyenko had announced
new members of the reshuffled government.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of cabinet members, including two deputy prime
ministers, were appointed on April 28. And the second, including a
deputy prime minister and 10 ministers, were appointed on April
30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
