<HEADLINE> Swaziland to Raise Spending on Government Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Despite warnings by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) against increasing public
expenditure, the Swazi government is to spend 18 million Rand
(3.6 million U.S. Dollars) this year on housing public servants.
</P>
<P>
Accountant-general David Dlamini recently disclosed that the
government had only 2.8 million Rand (560,000 Dollars) in rentals
for existing government housing, South African Press Association
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This was due to the failure of the government to update
rentals charged to public servants, Dlamini said.
</P>
<P>
He said that they were paying between 60 Rand (12 Dollars) and
100 Rand (20 Dollars) a month for houses which would fetch up to
3000 Rand (600 Dollars) a month on the open market.
</P>
<P>
Many public servants are reported to be subletting rooms in
their government-owned houses and using the proceeds to buy their
own houses. 
</P>
