<HEADLINE> S. African Minister Apologizes to Swaziland for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
has apologized to Swaziland following threats by South African
trade unions to blockade Swaziland's borders and cut electricity
supplies to force political change in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said that his
government dissociated itself from the threats made by the
Congress of South African Trade Unions (COSATU), one of the two
allies of the ruling African National Congress (ANC).
</P>
<P>
South Africa respects the sovereignty of Swaziland, South
African Press Association Tuesday quoted Nzo as saying. But it
did not mention when the minister made the apology.
</P>
<P>
The apology was conveyed via Chairman of the Swazi
Constitutional Commission, prince Mangaliso, on his return from a
visit to South Africa.  
