<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Addresses Reform of Grain Marketing System (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji has cited
the inevitability and urgency to restructure the nation's grain
marketing system.
</P>
<P>
Reform must be carried out in line with the principles of
separation of administrative functions from State-owned
grain companies, storage from management, central from local
responsibilities and new from old accounts, as well as improving
the pricing system for the grain market, said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who is also a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central
Committee, made the remarks at a national work conference on
restructuring the grain marketing system held between April 27-29,
</P>
<P>
The conference was the first held since the new central
government was formed early this year. Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao
delivered a report on reform during the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Reports presented during the conference indicated that China
has scored remarkable achievements in grain production in recent
years, as well as certain levels of progress in restructuring the
country's grain circulation system.
</P>
<P>
China has has established the State Special Grain Reserve
System, the Protective Pricing System, and the Grain Risk Fund,
</P>
<P>
However, the country's existing grain marketing system, which
is still a model of "sharing rice from the same big pot", features the
backward management on state grain firms, overlapping of
government and enterprise functions and overstaffing and rising
cost. Said factors have resulted in a shortage of grain purchase
funds, losses resulting from poor management and deficits which
have exceeded the financial capacity of the State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Capital Nurses Go on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Over 11,000 nurses in India's
capital New Delhi started their indefinite strike Tuesday
paralyzing the city's health services.
</P>
<P>
Health services in 28 government hospitals across the capital
were severely affected due to the strike. Many planned surgeries
were postponed and non-critical patients were discharged.
</P>
<P>
The strike has been called by the Delhi Nurses Union (DNU) to
protest the backtracking by the government on the agreement signed
with it last September on pay scales, promotions, allowances,
housing, filling up of vacancies and setting up of a nursing
directorate, DNU sources said here.
</P>
<P>
The Delhi government said Tuesday that it was open for talks
with agitating nurses in the capital over their demands, but ruled
out any pay hike.
</P>
<P>
Policemen were seen outside various hospitals to prevent any
untoward incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
