<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Ban Tobacco Advertizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- South African Health Minister
Nkosazana Zuma said she intended slapping a ban on tobacco
advertizing in an effort to stop the country's children from
smoking.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are underway to ban smoking in public and work places
to help reduce the dangers of passive smoking and protect the
right of non-smokers, the Southern African Broadcasting
Association Tuesday quoted the healath minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zuma, a medical doctor, said in a parliament debate that
although South Africa has made progress in raising people's
awareness on the dangers of smoking, 30 percent of its 41 million
people still smoke.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said her department is particularly concerned about the
number of women who smoke during pregnancy and of children who
puff in their early teens.
</P>
<P>
Recent surveys in South Africa showed seven out of 10 people
support government measures to make smoking more difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
