<HEADLINE> ADB Finances Agriculture Reforms in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has agreed to grant a technical assistance of 900,000 U.S. dollars
to assist the Nepali government in undertaking institutional
reforms in the agriculture sector, the ADB said Tuesday in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance will be used in supporting the reforms
of the agriculture institutions which include the fertilizer unit
at the Agriculture Ministry, the Agriculture Inputs Corporation
and the National Food Corporation, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the assistance is also for enhancing sustainable
infrastructure development in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Nepali government launched major policy reforms
for the liberalization of the agriculture sector under the
ADB-funded second agriculture program loan and in the context of
the Agriculture Perspective Plan (APP), the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The APP, introduced in Nepal in 1997, aims to boost agriculture
production through policy and institutional reforms and investment
in specific areas such as irrigation and rural infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that the continued stagnation in the country's
agriculture production has been attributed to ineffective public
interventions in the procurement and distribution of agriculture
inputs and outputs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
