<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanctions, No Practical Consequence to Pakistan: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for Pakistan's Foreign
Ministry has said that "the newest (U.S.) sanctions are of no
practical consequence as the KRL (Khan Research Laboratories) has
no dealings with American firms."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was referring Tuesday to the reports about the
imposition of U.S. restrictions pertaining to the Missile
Technology Control Regime (MTCR) on the Khan Research
Laboratories, named after Pakistan's eminent scientist Dr. Abdul
Qadeer Khan.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman recalled that Pakistan has, for a long time,
faced restrictions and sanctions under various U.S. laws "which
are one sided, discriminatory and unjust."
</P>
<P>
According to reports appearing on the major English newspapers
here Tuesday, the U.S. has slapped two-year sanctions against
Pakistan and a Korean organization for violating the MTCR.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. sanctions, effective from April 17, bar any U.S.
government contacts with the KRL and Korea's Changgwang Sinyong
Corporation (Mining Development Trading Corporation) of Korea for
two years, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The KRL developed and test-fired a surface-to-face missile
"Ghauri" on April 6. The missile has a range of 1,500 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
One report quoted the U.S. State Department as saying that the
sanctions were imposed because Pakistan had obtained missile parts
from Korea. Pakistan, however, has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government had imposed similar sanctions on Pakistan
in 1991 and 1993 for allegedly receiving missile technology from
other countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
