<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Hopeful of Progress After Talks With Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said Tuesday that he was hopeful the London peace talks
could achieve some progress in restoring the flagging Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said after a 75-minute meeting with British Prime
Minister Tony Blair early Tuesday that Israel was working to move
the process forward.
</P>
<P>
"We are working on it. We are working to move the process
forward and if everyone is committed to that, we can do it,"
Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said that Blair and Netanyahu, who
held talks Monday, exchanged views on all issues concerning the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli government spokesman David Bar-Illan told
BBC television Tuesday morning that progress had been made Monday
and predicted that the talks would not collapse.
</P>
<P>
"I think there has been quite a bit of progress. I think it is
not going to be a dramatic breakthrough nor is there going to be a
collapse of the talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinians have accused the Israelis of blocking
the crucial London talks by refusing to accept the American peace
initiative under which Israel will have to cede another 13 percent
of West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
"It is really taking too much time. I don't think they (the
Israelis) want to go through with it," Palestinian Planning and
Coordination Minister Nabil Shaath said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian President Yasser Arafat was in a very anxious
mood, said Shaath, who was worried that the whole peace process
might "go bust".
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, whose government is
striving to revive the peace talks, is due to hold another round
of talks with Netanyahu and Arafat in a bid to broker a pact.
</P>
<P>
The crucial London talks, which started early Monday, were
forced into a second day of heated argument after Albright failed
to bridge "significant gaps" between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process was plunged into a stalemate for
more than a year due to Israel's staunchly maintained Jewish
settlement projects in defiance of the opposition by the
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
