<HEADLINE> CPPCC Chairman Meets Australian Legislator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), met today with Australian Senate President
Margaret Reid.
</P>
<P>
Li noted the vast distance separating China and Australia, and
pointed to the quite different historical and cultural
backgrounds, as well as the differing customs and habits of the
two nations.
</P>
<P>
He said that bilateral relations have developed smoothly with
increasing exchanges of high-level visits and constantly expanding
economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that joint efforts will promote further
cooperation between various sectors in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Li said the two houses of the Australian parliament have
maintained close contacts and forged deep friendships with the
National People's Congress (NPC) and CPPCC.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed confidence that Reid's visit will be a catalyst
for the expanded growth of friendly cooperative relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He briefed the visitors on China's domestic situation by noting
the many changes which have taken place in the country in recent
years. He added that China still has a long way to go when
compared to developed countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the nation has developed smoothly in general terms, but
cautioned the China must be fully aware of lingering difficulties
as it continues to advance,
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely welcome comments and suggestion on our work from
foreign friends," said Li. However, with regard to actual
practice, China will proceed in line with specific conditions and
act in a prudent manner to ensure that no problems crop up in
providing subsistence for its over 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
Reid said her first visit to China has been short, but
nonetheless unforgettable, and noted that she has gained a better
understanding of China's development and changes.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that economic and trade cooperation is a major
aspect in relations between the two nations, and said Australia is
willing to further exchanges and cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
NPC Vice-Chairman Buhe also attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
