<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Pledges to Use IMF Fund to Strengthen Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will use
the second 3 billion U.S. dollars in IMF (International Monetary
Fund) aid to strengthen its foreign exchange reserves and balance
of payment, a senior official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government will not use the aid for market intervention,
aimed at propping up the ailing rupiah, Coordinating Minister for
Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita said after a
meeting with President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The minister was commenting on the IMF decision during a board
meeting in Washington on Monday (early Tuesday in Indonesia) to
release immediately 989.4 million U.S. dollars as part of the
second series of its 43 billion U.S. dollar bailout package for
Indonesia. The rest of the 3 billion U.S. dollars will be released
between May and July.
</P>
<P>
The release of fresh funds is expected to open the door to
funding from bilateral donors and other multilateral institutions.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar said from this month to July, Indonesia hopes to get
7.05 billion U.S. dollars in funds, including the 3 billion U.S.
dollars from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The rest is expected to come from the World Bank (one billion
dollars), Asian Development Bank (1.5 billion dollars), Japan (one
billion dollars) Malaysia (250 million dollars) and Australia (300
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Indonesia also hopes Singapore and Brunei would disburse their
loans shortly after the release of the second tranche of the IMF
aid, he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, in October last year, turned to the IMF after the
crash of the rupiah exposed weaknesses in its financial system.
</P>
<P>
It signed an economic reform package prescribed by the IMF, and
supported by the World Bank, the Asian Development Bank and
friendly countries, in exchange for 43 billion dollars in bailout
funds.
</P>
<P>
In December last year, the IMF disbursed the first 3 billion
dollars tranche of the bailout package.
</P>
<P>
The second tranche of the IMF aid was scheduled to be released
on March 15 but was delayed pending fresh negotiations on the
economic reform package to be implemented by Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
On April 8, the two sides signed a new agreement on the
economic and financial reforms in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
