<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Court Rejects Britain's "Mad Cow Disease" Argument </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Court of Justice has
rejected Britain's challenge to the legality of the European
Commission ban on British beef exports.
</P>
<P>
The court stressed that the commission, the executive body of
the 15-nation European Union, had acted in the interests of public
health.
</P>
<P>
But Britain argued that the commission had exceeded its power
in imposing the ban in March 1996 after London admitted a link
between "mad cow disease" and its human variation,
Creutzfeld-Jacob Disease (CJD).
</P>
<P>
Britain also claimed the EU ban was disproportionate to the
threat to human health posed by the bovine spongiform
encephalopathy (BSE), commonly known as mad cow disease, which
was first found in Britain in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission agreed earlier this year to allow
Northern Ireland to export certain types of beef that come from
herds with a traceable computer database to prove their BSE-free
status.
</P>
<P>
Britain has hitherto confirmed that 170,000 head of cattle had
contracted BSE and that CJD had claimed 23 people's lives so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
