<HEADLINE> Countdown Board Erected to Mark Macao's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A countdown board marking Macao's
return was erected at the eastern side of Tian'anmen Square here
today, 594 days before Macao's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Sixty Macao members and 40 inland members of the Preparatory
Committee for the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR)
attended today's unveiling ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The board, 16 meters tall and 9.6 meters wide, features the
designs of golden five-pointed stars and green lotuses, the
regional emblem of the Macao SAR, and also the characters which
read "Chinese Government Resumes Exercise of Sovereignty Over
Macao."
</P>
<P>
According to a designer of the board, its design reflects the
theme of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
Edmundo Ho Hau Wah, vice-chairman of the Preparatory Committee
for the Macao SAR, said that the countdown board not only reminds
the public of the time remaining prior to Macao's return to the
motherland on December 20, 1999, but also urges all members of the
Preparatory Committee to expedite work for the establishment of
the Macao SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao SAR Preparatory Committee Holds First Plenum (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In referring to the localization of civil servants and laws,
and the status of Chinese as an official language, Qian said the
three major issues are vital to the smooth transition and the
operation of the future SAR, and the Preparatory Committee will
attach adequate importance to them.
</P>
<P>
He said the return of Macao is an important component of
China's reunification cause, and the state will adopt the same
policies, which are "one country, two systems" and "a high-degree
of autonomy," toward Macao as Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Macao is smaller than Hong Kong in area and in population, he
said, adding that with good cooperation between China and
Portugal, Macao's transition should be smoother than Hong Kong's.
</P>
<P>
Qian reminded the committee members of the special nature and
complication of the Macao question, which includes many problems
in politics, economy, law, culture and history that were not
encountered in handling Hong Kong's transition.
</P>
<P>
He asked the Preparatory Committee members to solicit opinions
and suggestions put forward by Macao compatriots and create
favorable conditions for them to participate in the preparatory
work of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
This is not only the need to fulfill the current task, but also
will lay a foundation for the realization of "Macao people
governing Macao" and "a high-degree of autonomy" after 1999, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Qian also expressed the hope to cooperate with the Portuguese
government in handling transitional issues, saying it will comply
with the fundamental interests of both countries.
</P>
<P>
The successful practice of the "one country, two systems"
policy in Hong Kong has set an example for Macao's return, he
said, and he hopes the members of the Preparatory Committee will
make concerted efforts to contribute to China's peaceful
reunification cause.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was presided over by Xie Fei, vice-chairman of
the Preparatory Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
