<HEADLINE> Establishment of Global Information Infrastructure Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Kwong Ki-chi, Secretary for
Information Technology and Broadcasting of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), called on the telecommunications
industry to cooperate in the development of a global information
infrastructure as well as human resources and information
technology education.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 4th Asian Telecommunications Industry Exchange
Forum here Tuesday, Kwong said people in the Asia-Pacific region
needed to fully equip themselves for the journey to the
information world of tomorrow. It is necessary then to construct
the information infrastructure on which all other things rely.
</P>
<P>
"Technological advances in the last decade and the anticipated
developments in the future should provide us with the capability
to fully participate in the construction of a global information
infrastructure," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is now a matter of finding the right investment climate and
incentives to build the infrastructure," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the applications which make use of the
network, would be far more important than the network itself.
</P>
<P>
Electronic commerce was expected to make the most use of the
global information infrastructure and was a likely candidate to
help finance the building of the infrastructure, he said. But
development of other applications on the infrastructure for
interpersonal interaction is equally important.
</P>
<P>
Education and manpower training in information technology and
related applications was of paramount importance in the journey to
an information society, he added.
</P>
<P>
To make Hong Kong a leader in the information world of tomorrow
and to keep it in the forefront of the world in the development of
telecommunications, the SAR government had set up the new
Information Technology and Broadcasting Bureau with overall policy
responsibility for the coordination and development of
telecommunications, information technology applications, and
broadcasting in the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that this institutional change will enhance
coordination and efficiency in policy formulation and will help
promote the development of telecommunications, information
technology, as well as broadcasting in Hong Kong," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
