<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Automate Handling of Bulk Mail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The State Postal Bureau has decided
to phase out manual handling of bulk mail by introducing postage
machines at local post offices and offering them to users.
</P>
<P>
The decision will affect 70,000 post offices around the
country. Some 5,000 postage machines will be installed, worth
100-to-350 million yuan (12 million to 42 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Xu Kui, deputy director of the former General Administration of
Posts, said that modernization of counter service at post offices
calls for adoption of new technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Though China has already used machines to handle mail from
individual users, it still manually processes bulk mailings from
collective users such as companies and institutions.
</P>
<P>
He said that the introduction of postage machines will greatly
increase the speed of handling large batches of mail from major
users. The machines will help streamline the staff, improve the
efficiency of the post office and improve the administration of
the postage payment system, he said.
</P>
<P>
The State Postal Bureau began phasing out manual handling of
bulk mail from major users this month. It will first install
postage machines in post offices around the country and later
lease or sell them to collective users.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
