<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Gold Mines Double Quarterly Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's gold mines
doubled their earnings during the last quarter, and many expect
even better results this quarter as the higher gold price feeds
through into greater profits, analysts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Earnings grew from 98 million Rand (19.6 million U.S. Dollars)
to 196 million Rand (39.2 million Dollars), mainly because of a
dramatic fall in capital expenditure from 898 million Rand (179
million Dollars) to 698 million (139 million Dollars), The Star
reported.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said the fall in capital expenditure was
normal in the March quarter owing to the end of the tax year.
</P>
<P>
Profit for the gold sector as a whole rose 19 percent during
the quarter from 937 million Rand (187 million Dollars) to 1,114
million Rand (223 million Dollars), the report said.
</P>
<P>
Margins extended out from 306 Rand (61 Dollars) an ounce in
the last quarter in 1997 to 318 Rand (64 Dollars) in the first
three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
This was despite large-scale retrenchments in the industry and
deep restructuring, analysts said. Retrenchment costs were
"huge", and this led to profit before tax edging up "slightly "
from 778 million Rand (155 million Dollars) to 782 million Rand
(156 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
It would have been larger without these costs, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the other figures for the gold industry were much
improved during the quarter, with costs falling from 207 Rand
(41.4 Dollars) a ton to 202 Rand (40.4 Dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Cotton Yield to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Despite the price drop of about 16
percent, Mozambique's cotton production is expected to rise to
80,000 tons over the 70,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The price set for the year's cotton is 2,500 Meticals per
kilogram (one U.S Dollar equals about 11,650 Meticals) from the
current 3,300 Meticals a kilogram, the Mozambican Institute of
Cotton (IAM) said in a suggestion report to the government.
</P>
<P>
Eugenio Gove, director of the IAM said the reason for the
price adjustment is the low demand at the world cotton market.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is the third cotton producer in the world, with its
peak production of 140,000 tons in 1973 and the lowest annual
production of 5,200 tons in 1985, the lowest in the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
About 200,000 farmers are growing cotton in central and
northern part of the country, with a cotton growing acreage of
130,000 hectares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
