<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Curb Increasing Medical Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The South African Health
Department is to introduce a legislation aimed at addressing the
rocketing health costs.
</P>
<P>
Addressing parliament during a debate on the 1998-99 health
budget Monday, Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma said the
ever-increasing medical aid costs had become "a real crisis" in
the industry.
</P>
<P>
Zuma attributed the rise in medical aid costs to, among
others, the inappropriate use of expensive technology as well as
incorrect diagnosis by doctors.
</P>
<P>
She said her department would develop a comprehensive social
security system which would help the poor.
</P>
<P>
The government reportedly would also present to parliament
tobacco bills aimed at preventing children from smoking,
protecting the right of non-smokers and helping smokers who want
to stop smoking.
</P>
<P>
Zuma also called on politicians to join the fight against
HIV-Aids and mobilize the people of the whole country to take
precautions to prevent the deadly disease from spreading.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that 1,500 people were infected daily and two
million South Africans were already infected, Zuma told
parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
