<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's High Interest Rates Stall Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- South African government and
the private sector said Monday that the country's high real
interest rates and tough anti-inflation monetary policy were
getting in the way of an "investment boom".
</P>
<P>
In separate submissions to parliament, both the Trade and
Industry Department and the South African Chamber of Business
(SACOB) targeted the high real interest rates of about 10 percent
as problematic in promoting investment, job creation and growth,
Business Day paper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The department said compared with its competitors' rates of
between two and five percent, South Africa's real interest rates
are too high and are "constraining a more widespread and
substantial investment boom".
</P>
<P>
The department said evidence also disproved the theory that
high interest rates lead to more labor-intensive investment
</P>
<P>
It said the country, having had high interest rates for some
years because of concerns over inflation, should now decrease
rates rapidly, providing a boost to industry in times of low
demand.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures showed that South Africa's producer inflation
fell to a 28-year low in March at 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
SACOB said the high real cost of capital in the country, which
was 40 percent more than in Europe, was a "significant factor".
</P>
<P>
The SACOB submission noted that the Growth, Employment and
Redistribution Strategy (GEAR), the government's macro-economic
policy, set a target of five percent for the real bank rate at
the end of last year. But the rate was 8.3 percent at that time.
</P>
<P>
The rate had risen to just below 10 percent this year despite
the GEAR target of 4 percent for this year, it said.
</P>
<P>
SACOB also claimed red tape in the trade department's
administration of export and investment incentive programs had
driven investors to South Africa's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
It criticized the department's supply side measures,
particularly the tax holiday scheme, saying it was a "relatively
poor instrument for promoting investment".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
