<HEADLINE> Iron Reserves in Iran Reach 1 Billion Tonnes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The proven reserves of iron ores in
Iran reached 1 billion tonnes, providing the country with good
potential to develop steel industry, the morning newspaper Iran
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The daily pointed out that the abundance in iron resources has
contributed to a considerable boost in the steel industry during
the past decade, promoting Iran's annual steel production from
920,800 tonnes in 1987 to 6.2 million tonnes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, steel production was estimated at around 7 million
tonnes, the newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Minister of Mines and Metals Eshaq Jahangiri disclosed
last week that Iran's steel exports reached some 830,000 tonnes
during the past Iranian calendar year, which ended in March 20,
fetching 374 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country is expected to produce 10 million tonnes of steel
this year and earn 460 million dollars from steel production, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also stated that Tehran planned to further raise the annual
steel production capacity to 12 million tonnes in the coming three
years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the daily reported that Iran is also rich in natural
gas and coal, adding that Iran has 15-20 percent of the world
total gas reserves while its proven oil reserves stood at about
190 million tonnes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
