<HEADLINE> Uganda Airlines Goes Privatized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The sale agreement for Uganda
Airlines' shares in Entebbe Handling Services Limited (ENHAS) has
been signed in Kampala among strong protests from its staff.
</P>
<P>
The stake buyers made a two billion Ugandan Shillings (2
million U.S. Dollars) down payment for the 45 percent shares in
the company, with the Efforte Corporation and Global Airlines
holding 20 percent each and Sabena Airlines having the remaining
five percent, The New Vision paper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Privatization Unit Director Michael Opagi said the buyers were
given a maximum of three months to complete the payment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at a seminar on Uganda Airlines' privatization last
Wednesday, the sale of the shares was sharply criticized by the
workers. They blamed the Privatization Unit for not consulting
the staff before selling off the shares.
</P>
<P>
The airlines' head of commercial services, Joshua Mugizi,
wondered why the Privatization Unit sold the shares at a
give-away price when Dairo Air Services was ready to offer about
6.5 billion Ugandan Shillings (6.5 million U.S. Dollars) for the
purchase.
</P>
<P>
He said Alliance Air had also planned to buy the shares at 4.5
billion Shillings (4.5 million U.S. Dollars) but they were not
considered.
</P>
<P>
But the Enterprise Development Project Executive Director
Leonard Muganwa denied ever receiving any offers from the two
airlines, arguing that ENHAS stake holders had pre-emptive rights
to acquire the shares before other interested buyers could be
invited.
</P>
<P>
The staff could not be consulted during the sale because the
divested 45 percent shares belonged to the corporation and not
workers, he added.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is currently launching a privatization drive and is
becoming more open to the outside world. It has recently decided
to sell some shares in big state-run businesses like the Uganda
Commercial Bank, Uganda Telecom and the Uganda Airlines,
attracting investors from around the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
