<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Germany's ruling Christian Democratic Union (DCU) Monday
kicked off a campaign to promote the euro, in a bid to rally the
Germans around the single currency and to convince them that
Helmut Kohl is capable to run it safely in this new adventure.
</P>
<P>
But Kohl was strongly criticized by the financial circles, the
press and the oppositions for agreeing to a compromise with France
over the presidency of the European Central Bank (ECB).
</P>
<P>
-- Algerian Security Forces have killed nearly 100 Islamic
extremists over the past six days in operations against the Armed
Islamic Group in the western part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The psychodrama last weekend around the designation of the
president of the European Central Bank did not disturb the market
of exchanges and interest rates. The stocks continued to escalate
in the indexes of Wall Street, while the CAC 40 index in Paris
gained 2.4 percent and the index in Frankfurt by 4.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Maurice Papon, who was former chief of the Paris Police
Department, said in an interview with Le Figaro that the figure of
casualties provided by an official report on the 1961 suppression
of Algerian demonstrators in Paris was correct. The official
report said that dozens -- instead of hundreds as some claimed --
of Algerians were killed by police on October 17 and 18, 1961,
during a crackdown on demonstrators supporting the National
Liberation Front (FLN) of Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Papon was sentenced last month to 10 years in prison for crimes
against humanity he was convicted to have committed when he was
number three of the collaborationist regime in Gironde, southwest
France, during the German occupation. He deported 6,900 Jews to
Nazi death camps from Gironde. 
</P>
