<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Newspapers Hail Establishment of SARPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Leading Chinese newspapers in Macao
all carried editorials on Tuesday, hailing the establishment of
the Macao Special Administrative Region Preparatory Committee
(SARPC).
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News said in its editorial that the SARPC
establishment marks the start of the preparatory work for the
Macao SAR (special administrative region), turning a new page in
the history of Macao.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment will help increase liaison with Macao
residents, and map out proposals for a smooth handover and the
establishment of the Macao SAR," it said.
</P>
<P>
The committee, set up in Beijing Tuesday morning, has 100
members, with 60 from Macao and 40 from China's mainland. China
will resume the exercise of sovereignty over Macao on December 20,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The editorial urged Macao residents to take an active part in
the work of the committee by submitting their opinions and
suggestions and supporting the work of the committee.
</P>
<P>
It expressed the belief that the committee will prove again the
success of Deng Xiaoping's theory of "one country, two systems" in
Macao, saying the committee can draw upon the successful
experience of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
preparatory committee and start from the actual situation in
Macao.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the committee will work hard in the national
interests of China, and work strictly in accordance with the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration and the Macao Basic Law," it
said.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese daily, Tai Chung Pou, said the SARPC is a "big
and happy thing" long expected by Macao residents. It also urged
all Macao residents including those non-Chinese nationals to air
their opinions to the committee.
</P>
<P>
It said that the committee will not be a second power center in
Macao, but rather a body conducive to Macao's smooth transition
and development.
</P>
<P>
The Correio Sino-Macaense Daily said that the committee will
successfully accomplish its mission as it is guided by the Macao
Basic Law and can draw upon the experience of Hong Kong SAR
preparatory committee.
</P>
<P>
It is under the correct leadership of the Central Government of
China and has the support of the residents of Macao, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The "Cheng Pou" newspaper said that it hopes members from Macao
 and China's mainland can work in good coordination so that the
committee can lay a "solid and sound track" for the realization of
 "one country, two systems" and "Macao people governing Macao."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
