<HEADLINE> Parliamentary Crisis Solved in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen and deposed First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh
reached a conciliation Thursday on the election procedure dispute,
thus avoiding a National Assembly (parliament) crisis.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen told the reporters after an assembly session that he
had called Ranariddh Tuesday, asking him to send assembly
members to attend the parliamentary session for the amendment to
the Election Law.
</P>
<P>
In the call, Hun Sen told Ranariddh that "for the people and
the country, we should cooperate."
</P>
<P>
The second prime minister also said that they agreed the
ballots will be brought to the communalities for counting instead
of being counted in villages, but not in district or provincial
capitals as those opposition parliamentary members demanded.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers loyal to Ranariddh and Buddhist Liberal Democratic
Party founder Son Sann have been boycotting the assembly meetings
in the hope of holding negotiations on the disputed electional
procedure.
</P>
<P>
Due to the boycott, a session of the National Assembly
scheduled for Monday failed to meet the quorum that requires the
attendance of 84 members. Only 77 members appeared at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
If it continues, the boycott could force a delay of the
election now scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
However, after the aborted session on Monday, Hun Sen warned
that if the general election can not be held before September 24,
on which the term of the current parliament is to expire, the
National Assembly will be dissolved automatically.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen is expected to leave for Bangkok Wednesday for a
two-day official visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
