<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A factory, with an annual production capacity of
30,000 tonnes of feed concentrate for livestock and fish, went
into operation Monday.
</P>
<P>
Its fodder will serve the markets in Jordan, Sudan, Yemen, Iraq
and Syria, semi-official Jordan Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and the United States Agency for International
Development (USAID) signed an agreement Monday to provide 60 million
dollars for the government's reform campaign.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used for diversifying maritime activities to
break state monopoly, readjusting customs tariffs, reducing budget
deficit, decreasing state-owned companies' debts and intensifying
regulations to protect investment.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has sounded alarm against the sharp decline in
investments in Arab countries, which dropped to 21 percent of the
gross national products in 1996 from 72 percent in 1990, the
Egyptian Gazette reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar here Monday, Egyptian Economy Minister Boutros
Ghali attributed the plunge to sluggish economy and the wide gap
between investments and savings in these countries.
</P>
<P>
The savings can cover only 60 percent of the funds needed for
investment, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ghali also said that the rapid growth of population in most
Arab countries has aggravated food shortage there.
</P>
<P>
The annual natural population growth rate in Arab countries is
three percent on average.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran is planning to build a 300-kilometer pipeline
from the Caspian Sea port city Neka in Mazadaran province to the
capital Tehran for transporting Caspian oil to Europe, the Jomhuri
Islami reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline, with a daily capacity of 380,000 barrels, will be
completed in two and a half years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
