<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relocation of HK Airport Starts Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The process of relocation of the
Hong Kong International Airport from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok will
start on Wednesday to be consistent with new airport opening on
July 6, a senior Airport Authority official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented move comprises of five phases over a
three-month period, of which the night move during the late hours
of July 5 and the early hours of July 6 is "the most critical", AA
Corporate Development Director Clinton Leeks said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an Airport Consultative Committee plenary meeting.
Leeks said, the objectives of the relocation are "to achieve a
seamless transfer of airport operation from Kai Tak to Chek Lap
Kok and to ensure that Hong Kong, at all times, has a fully
functional airport whether at Kai Tak or Chek Lap Kok."
</P>
<P>
Detailed planning of the relocation began in late 1996, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The dates and times of the various phases are as follows:
pre-advance move, from May 6 to June 4; advance move, from June 5
to June 21; main body move, from June 22 to 17:30 hours July 5;
night move, from 17:30 hours July 5 to 06:30 hours July 6; and
follow-on move till August 5.
</P>
<P>
"The relocation exercise is being planned on the basis of three
inter-linked operations: the departure from Kai Tak; the journey
from Kai Tak to the new airport, including allocation of time
slots for moves by road, sea and air; reception and distribution
at Chek Lap Kok," Leeks said.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the movement of vehicles and equipment will take
place by road, but will be supplemented, especially in the final
stages, by barge transportation and in night move by air
transport.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 10,000 land movements, 70 barge movements
and 30 aircraft movements will be required through the exercise,
said Leeks.
</P>
<P>
The success of the move requires close coordination between the
AA, various government departments such as Police, Transport
Department and Marine Department, and all business partners, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Leeks also told of contingency planning in case of bad weather
as early July is prone to typhoon and rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
The postponement of the final stages of the move will be
considered if there is any likelihood of winds high enough, for
example, 40 kilometers per hour or above, to necessitate partial
closure of the Lantau Link, a major road link between Kowloon and
the new airport.
</P>
<P>
The hoisting of a No. 3 typhoon signal will also mean the
automatic suspension of the sea move as barge operators' insurance
is no longer valid under the conditions, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
