<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Information System Urged to Promote HK's Hotel Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government should establish a
comprehensive hotel development information system in its efforts
to promote local hotel business, the Hong Kong Tourist Association
(HKTA) suggested Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The system will provide market data to developers and the
industry, and assist the SAR government in the planning of sites
for hotel development, according to the results of a study
released by HKTA.
</P>
<P>
The data should be reviewed every six months and the findings
made public, HKTA said.
</P>
<P>
"Study on the Demand and Supply of Hotels in Hong Kong",
commissioned by the association, was a follow-up to
recommendations in the Association's "Visitor and Tourism Study
for Hong Kong" completed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Study takes into account committed development projects as
well as hotels currently holding planning or building
applications.
</P>
<P>
Hotel development decisions are driven not only by
tourism-related factors, but also by underlying real estate
considerations, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Policy initiatives implemented by the government have also
resulted in increased interest in hotel development since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The designation of hotel use in statutory zoning plans will
facilitate the emergence of a land market for hotel projects, the
study said. It also recommended that the designation of
site-specific zoning continue to be part of the plan-making
process.
</P>
<P>
The study noted that, in the long term, while there will be an
increase in the number of hotels in the peripheral urban areas
along the Mass Transit Railways (MTR) lines, the supply of hotel
sites in the Central Business District (CBD) and prime urban sites
may not be sufficient to cope with the long-term growth in demand.
</P>
<P>
The study suggested that the government consider the
application of specific zoning to satisfy the projected long-term
demand for top-quality hotels in the CBD over the next five
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
