<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, China to Enhance Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh Prime Minister Nurlan
Balgimbaev said his forthcoming visit to China will give a fresh
impetus to the development of relations between Kazakhstan and
China.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua before leaving for China Thursday,
Balgimbaev said the Kazakh-Chinese ties have made remarkable
progress in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the progress to the friendly and good-neighborly
relations between the two countries, the statement by the major
nuclear powers including China on providing security guarantee to
Kazakhstan, confidence-building measures taken in the military
field along the border areas of the two countries, regular
contacts between leaders of the two countries and the signing of
important documents on furthering bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Speaking highly of the bilateral economic and trade
cooperation, Balgimbaev said that China is Kazakhstan's biggest
trading partner in Asia and Kazakhstan ranks second only to Russia
in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) that have trade
ties with China.
</P>
<P>
China will remain as the most potential trading partner to
Kazakhstan in the future, and the economic and trade cooperation
between the two countries will be further expanded, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has planned to set up an automobile joint venture and
build hotels and trading centers in Kazakhstan, he said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, a number of documents on promoting
cooperation between the two countries will be signed, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the domestic situation, Balgimbaev said Kazakhstan's
economic policy has been consistent in recent years. Its
macro-economy is stable, the decline in production has been
curbed, a steady economic growth ensured and the standard of
living improved.
</P>
<P>
He said six years of development in the Commonwealth of
Independent States shows that the road is not even to a realistic
and efficient integration beneficial to all its member states.
</P>
<P>
He believed that integration should be achieved first of all in
economy and then extended to other fields. That's why Kazakhstan
has proposed the establishment of a unified economy in the CIS.
</P>
<P>
Balgimbaev, 51, a former minister of the Oil and Gas Industry,
was appointed as prime minister on October 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
