<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Million HK Dollars Worth of Pirated VCDs Seized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Police Monday night
closed down a distribution center of pirated video compact disks
(VCDs) following the arrest of two men and the seizure of 130,000
pirated VCDs in Kwai Chung, New Territories.
</P>
<P>
While patrolling in Kwai Chung Sunday night, police officers
spotted two men acting suspiciously at a car park of an industrial
building.
</P>
<P>
During a search of a light goods vehicle parked nearby, police
found two master disks for manufacturing pirated VCDs and a large
quantity of VCD covers. Police later located about 10,000 pirated
VCDs at a lift lobby inside the building.
</P>
<P>
Police on Monday night searched a flat on the third floor of
the industrial building and seized about 120,000 pirated VCDs. A
large quantity of VCD covers and packing materials were also
found. The haul could fetch about two million HK dollars (256,000
U.S. dollars) in retail markets.
</P>
<P>
The two men, aged 22 and 27 respectively, are now being
detained for interrogation and the case will later be handed over
to the Hong Kong Customs and Excise Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
