<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Southernmost Island Province Attracting Taiwanese Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, May 5 (Xinhua) -- China's southernmost island province
of Hainan has attracted nearly 200 Taiwanese-funded agriculture
enterprises and 150 million US dollars of their investment.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises have at least 13,000 hectares of land in almost
all Hainan's cities and counties producing fruits, flowers, and
aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
Ever since a Taiwan farmer leased 55 hectares of land here in
1988, other Taiwanese-funded enterprises have been following suit
and, although it was somewhat affected by the financial crisis in
East and Southeast Asia, Taiwanese farmers still show confidence
in their investment in Hainan.
</P>
<P>
They say that Hainan has advantages in its climate, available
land, cheap labor, and capital, and still has more than a million
hectares of arable land ready for use.
</P>
<P>
Investing in Hainan is one way for Taiwanese agro-businesses to
enter mainland markets. And their fruits and flowers have been
exported not only to the cities of Beijing, Shanghai, and
Guangzhou, but to Japan and Europe as well.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, the provincial government has given "national
treatment" to Taiwanese investors, attracting even more funds from
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Some experts say that agricultural co-operation across the
Taiwan Straits has great potential. The present 150 million US
dollars worth of Taiwanese investment is only a small part of the
7.5 billion US dollars worth of overseas investment in the
province during the past 10 years. Most Taiwanese-funded
agriculture enterprises are solely managed by Taiwan investors and
are involved in planting and cultivation, with only a few involved
in technology, processing, transportation, and sales.
</P>
<P>
They also say that a greater effort should be made in
increasing cooperation. It is learned that the provincial
government has applied to the State Council for a
Hainanese-Taiwanese experimental agricultural development center
and more policy support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 09:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Decides to Join International Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel has decided to join the
International Development Association (IDA) of the World bank with
the aim of facilitating access to other world institutions and
helping Israeli firms reach to more countries.
</P>
<P>
The decision came following a series of meetings between
Israeli Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman and the president of the
IDA, James D. Wolfensohn, local daily Haaretz reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Israel believes that joining the IDA will
reinforce its standing in the international community, thus making
easier its entry into other important global institutions.
</P>
<P>
Though Israel has to pay for the IDA membership 1 million
dollars a year, Israeli companies will be able, in return, to bid
for tenders issued by the bank, which total some 6 billion dollars
annually.
</P>
<P>
The IDA membership will also open a vast market of projects to
Israel's companies, some in countries in which Israel has not yet
been active, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The IDA is the economic aid arm of the World Bank. It provides
subsidized aid to some 80 poor countries with a total population
of about 3.5 billion people -- 60 percent of the world's total
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
