<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhang Wannian Meets U.S. Assistant Secretary of Defense  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- China always values and takes a
positive attitude toward the growth of Sino-American military
relations, said General Zhang Wannian in a meeting with visiting
U.S. Assistant Secretary of Defense Franklin Kramer here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, vice-chairman of the Chinese Central Military
Commission, said President Jiang Zemin paid a successful state
visit to the United States last fall. Jiang and U.S. President
Bill Clinton affirmed their joint commitment to set up a
constructive and strategic partnership between the two countries
oriented toward the 21st century, which laid down the framework
and direction for the development of bilateral relations in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also reached common understanding on
cooperation between the armed forces of the two countries, Zhang
said, adding that China is ready to make concerted efforts with
the United States in a bid to bring these understandings to
fruition.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the healthy development of relations between Chinese
and American armed forces not only is in accord with the
fundamental interests of citizens of the two countries, but is
also conducive to peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific region
and the world.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of future exchanges between the two armed forces,
he said, the Chinese side is willing in the spirit of equality and
mutual benefit to actively consult and discuss with its US
counterpart the possibilities of cooperation in various fields to
promote the further advancement of relations between the two
countries and their armed forces.
</P>
<P>
With regard to President Clinton's upcoming state visit to
China, Zhang expressed his conviction that this visit will inject
new energy into Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhang Wannian Meets U.S. Assistant Secretary Of Defense (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kramer said that Jiang Zemin's visit to the United States last
October yielded important results and the joint commitments
affirmed by the two presidents to develop constructive and
strategic partnership that laid the groundwork for long-term
development of bilateral relations. The US is anticipating a
successful visit by President Clinton to China, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kramer noted that the establishment of long-term, friendly and
constructive relations between the United States and China
conforms to the interests of both countries as they are both large
nations and standing members of U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the United States recognizes the
important common interests with China, and that US hopes that
relations between the two armed forces can be improved in
conjunction with the growth of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Kramer conveyed to Zhang a former letter of invitation to visit
the United States from U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen and
said he hoped Zhang would visit after President Clinton's trip to
keep the momentum going between the two countries and their armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
Zhang expressed his appreciations and said he expected his
official visit to the United States would come within the year at
a time convenient to both sides.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant General Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of the General
Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army, and U.S. Ambassador
to China James Sasser were present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Xiong also met with Kramer and his party this morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Exchanges Between China's Urban, Rural Areas (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- More and more city people are moving
to the countryside for business opportunities, while many Chinese
farmers are still flooding to the cities for better-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
The city dwellers come to the countryside not only for fresh
air, delicacy of vegetables, and solitude, but also to make a
fortune.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Dijun is one such new rural resident. He used to work in
a machine-building plant in Shijiazhuang City, capital of north
China's Hebei Province. But he quitted and leased a barren
mountain, which covers about 70 hectares in Pingshan County near
Shijiazhuang.
</P>
<P>
"I was employed as a consultant by a township enterprise in
Pingshan County several year ago and found the county is rich in
natural resources and cheap labor, so I decided to settle down
here," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
But Zhang is not the only one who quit a job in town to move to
countryside. A substantial part of China's 10 million hectares of
barren mountains are now operated by people from cities, not local
farmers, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Also in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, some
graduates from Beijing and Qinghua universities bought 4,000
hectares of land in the Dayao Mountain area at a cost of five
million yuan years ago. Now their farm has become the area's best.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, enterprises in urban areas have been extending their
arms into the countryside seeking lower production costs. The
Shuanghui Group, one of the largest Chinese producers of ham and
sausage in central China's Henan Province, has established several
farms raising livestock in eight counties.
</P>
<P>
Another ham producer, the "Three Deer" Group in Hebei Province,
used 20 million yuan to support 20,000 local farmers to raise
livestock in 24 counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Exchanges Between China's Urban, Rural Areas (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the same time, many Chinese farmers have entered cities,
working in construction, manufacturing and retail.
</P>
<P>
According to sources with the Ministry of Agriculture, China
now has 60 million farmers working in cities, accounting for 13
percent of the total rural labor.
</P>
<P>
Wang Daming, a farmer of Wangying Village of Laohekou City in
central China's Hubei Province, rented in the city a box-making
plant that was near bankruptcy. He has turned losses into profits,
and earns 500,000 yuan in pre-tax income every year.
</P>
<P>
"This, the dual migration of people, will lead to an economic
integration between rural and urban areas, which used to be
separate economic units before," said Xu Pengxian, a researcher
for the China Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
City dwellers bring new operation methods, new ideas, money and
technology when they move to countryside. They help accelerate the
industrialization of rural areas and increase exchanges between
cities and rural areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Xu said it was because of the rapid development of township
enterprises in recent years that rural and urban people could
migrate freely.
</P>
<P>
The bulging pockets of farmers have also enhanced their
position in the urbanization of rural areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Yuncheng City in northwest China's Shanxi Province
have invested nearly 500 million yuan in urban construction since
1985 when expansion was approved. Yuncheng now is called "a new
city on farmers' shoulders." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
