<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Info Industry Beats Expectations, Says Top Intel Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Chinese economic
official and a world-famous U.S. entrepreneur this morning shared
their views on trends in the information industry and discussed
possible cooperation between their two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Peiyan, Chinese minister of the State Development Planning
Commission, said the information industry has propelled global
growth and China's domestic economy. He added that the sector has
been a major cause of growth for China.
</P>
<P>
A technical guru himself, Zeng asked cyberspace celebrity
Andrew Grove, president of Intel Corp., to brief him on the latest
developments in computer technology. "Now engaged in routine
office work and meetings, I would like to recharge myself," Zeng
said.
</P>
<P>
Grove responded by predicting that there will be "more than one
billion personal computers inter-connected" in the next century,
thus fundamentally changing the landscape of the world's economy
and trade, and even people's lifestyles. "This is not just a
vision, but a reality turned bigger and bigger," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his eyes, Grove said the development of the information
industry in China is also "ahead of expectations."
</P>
<P>
Intel's business in the fast-growing Chinese economy also is
exceeding expectations, he said. In his current China trip, Grove
will unveil a big research-and-development center in Beijing. An
Intel manufacturing plant with an investment of 200 million
U.S. dollars will be in operation "four months ahead of schedule
with the support of the Chinese government," Grove said.
</P>
<P>
Grove said he hopes China becomes a leading participant in the
application of new technologies. Some local companies have already
done so, he said. Grove said he will attend a ceremony marking the
production of the one millionth China-made PC produced by the
Legend Group, the country's leading PC manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government always takes an active and supportive
attitude to the investment of high-tech corporations in China,"
Zeng said. To encourage such investment, the Chinese government
has resumed a preferential taxation policy for importing high-tech
equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said China's vast market and the recent restructuring of
its government bodies also presents opportunities for overseas
companies.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese leaders attach importance to high-tech
development," Zeng said, adding that Chinese president Jiang Zemin
in recent years has met with many high-tech entrepreneurs and
experts.
</P>
<P>
Zeng then picked up a copy of "Time" celebrating Grove as the
magazine's "Man of the Year" in 1997 for his contribution to the
information industry. "It is an honor for all working in the
industry," Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
Grove said he was excited to share "similar views" in many
fields with Chinese officials. He then demonstrated
photo-recognition software using high-performance Intel-made
chips.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Grove and his party met with Wu Jichuan, Chinese
minister of Information Industry, and exchanged views on the
future trends and applications of the high-tech industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
