<HEADLINE> U.S. Citizen Honored for Charitable Educational Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Wu Zhongliang, a U.S. citizen of
Chinese origin, was recently honored as a "citizen of Neijiang" by
the city government in southwest China's Sichuan Province for his
decade-long efforts to help the province develop education.
</P>
<P>
Wu, whose ancestral home is Neijiang, settled in the United
States in 1968. He has donated more than six million yuan (about
750,000 U.S. dollars) to set up 14 schools in the province. His
total donation for education is the biggest the province ever
received from an overseas compatriot.
</P>
<P>
He began his charitable efforts in 1986, then established
kindergartens, primary schools, high schools and homes for the
elderly in Neijiang. He participated in a charitable project last
year, establishing 10 schools in Neijiang, and set up an
educational fund of more than 2 million yuan (240,000 US dollars)
to encourage excellent local teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
The charitable project sponsored by the provincial government
in 1994 has received overseas donations exceeding 15 million yuan
(1.8 million US dollars) and has built 66 primary schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
