<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Coal Port To Mark Centennial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- China's largest coal port --
Qinhuangdao port on Bohai Bay in the northern part of the country
-- will celebrate its 100th anniversary in June.
</P>
<P>
Opened by the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) in 1898, Qinhuangdao was
the first port of its kind in China's history. All the ports
preceding Qinhuangdao were forced to open by foreign invaders.
</P>
<P>
In its 100 years, Qinhuangdao port has functioned as a hub of
coal transport from the mines in the north to the urbanized south.
</P>
<P>
China is rich in coal resources, but they are unevenly
distributed. Coal production centers are concentrated in north and
northwest China, while the economically developed southeast
regions run short of coal.
</P>
<P>
Situated at the juncture of north and northeast China,
Qinhuangdao is a natural choice as the coal transportation hub.
</P>
<P>
To transport more coal from the production centers in the north
to the south, China has invested 12 billion yuan since 1978 in
building four large coal wharves in Qinhuangdao port, together
with the Datong-Qinhuangdao multiple railway to speed up coal
transportation. By these actions, a complete system for coal
transportation has been formed.
</P>
<P>
By July 1997, Qinhuangdao port had built four modern coal
wharves, with a yearly handling capacity of 106 million tons of
coal.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, Qinhuangdao port will have 60 berths from the current
38, with a yearly handling capacity of 124.8 million tons. At that
point, Qinhuangdao is expected to become one of the world's top
coal ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
