<HEADLINE> Sex Education Urged in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Family Life Movement of Zambia
(FLMZ) has called on parents to freely discuss sexual issues with
their children for the benefit of the young generation.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by FLMZ Deputy Provincial Program officer,
Regina Lungu, during the opening of a five-day workshop held here
Monday, according to Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
She said there is need to empower the parents with
communication skills aimed at creating dialog between the parents
and their children over sex education.
</P>
<P>
She urged the parents who have a tendency of failing to dialog
with their children over the critical sexuality issues to reflect
and stop the habit.
</P>
<P>
Lungu told the participants that unlike in the past where sex
education was a taboo among family members, families should now
be able to discuss the topic openly.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, parish priest Edgar Pillet said there is
need to educate children when they are young.
</P>
<P>
This will enable them to dialog with parents when they reach
the youthful stage, he said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is also attended by representatives of the girl
child adolescent reproductive health and the United Nations fund
for population activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
