<HEADLINE> Cisco Systems Buys Israeli Software Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The international communications
giant Cisco Systems has announced to spend 50 million U.S. dollars
to buy Class Data Systems, an Israeli software firm, local daily
Haaretz reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that this is Cisco's first acquisition of a
company in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The transaction between Cisco and Class Data is expected to be
finalized before June, Haaratz said, adding a team from Cisco had
arrived in Israel early this week to complete the transaction.
</P>
<P>
Cisco is a global leader in networking for the Internet,
controlling about 70 percent of the communications routes to the
Internet worldwide. Class Data, which was founded in 1996,
provides software solutions and management services for Internet.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Gal, director-general of Cisco's Israeli branch, said
that the acquisition of Class Data was a breakthrough for Cisco
and that it was the first time the international company decided
to purchase a high-tech company outside Northern American. 
</P>
</TEXT>
