<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Import Two Million Tons of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Southern African Development
Community (SADC) countries need to import more than two million
tons of maize this year to cover the shortage of the staple food
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The latest monthly issue of the regional Food Security Update
reaching here Tuesday said the maize output was forecast at 15.24
million to 16.14 million tons compared with last year's actual
output of 17.05 million tons in 11 of the 14 countries.
</P>
<P>
Only Mozambique and South Africa were projected to have maize
surplus while production was forecast to increase in Angola,
Malawi, Mozambique, Swaziland and Zambia where rainfall was
normal or above normal.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho, South Africa and Zimbabwe were adversely affected by
delayed rains and dry spells in February while Tanzania will have
low yield because of excessive rains.
</P>
<P>
Maize is the staple food in most parts of Southern Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
