<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty-Stricken Population Drops in Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The poverty-stricken population in
China's urban areas shrank by 80,000 last year, according to a
report released this week by the State Statistical Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The poverty-stricken population in urban China is now
estimated at 11.68 million, accounting for 4.1 percent of the
country's urban residents.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's random survey of 17,000 urban families shows that
85.5 percent, or 9.97 million, of the urban poor population live
in central and western China, where economies are underdeveloped.
</P>
<P>
Of them, 6.8 million are in central China and 3.17 million in
western China, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the 1996 figure, the proportion of
poverty-stricken people in China's urban population in 1997
decreased by 0.5 percentage points in eastern China, and 0.8
percentage points in western China. However, central China
reported an increase of 2.3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 61.47 percent of the poverty-stricken
people in urban China are victims of the ongoing depression in
state-owned enterprises, which has caused a swelling unemployment
rate in cities.
</P>
<P>
This "temporary unemployed population" will shrink quickly, as
the country completes reforms in the state enterprises and
provides more job opportunities than before, the report stated.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the government at all levels should give economic
development a top priority as an effective means to eradicate
poverty in cities, in addition to establishing a far-reaching
social welfare system and providing more professional training for
unskilled laborers, the report stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
