<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Expand Defense Exchange with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan is prepared to expand its
exchanges with China in the defense sector, according to Fumio
Kyuma, director-general of the Japanese Defense Agency.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an audience at the Chinese People's Liberation Army
University of National Defense, Kyuma said that exchanges between
defense sectors in the two countries would contribute to regional
peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
He said that the National Institute for Defense Studies of the
Japanese Defense Agency and China's University of National Defense
would engage in exchanges. He added that both sides can also
cooperate in medical science.
</P>
<P>
Kiyuma said he hopes that warships of the two countries would
visit each other in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
As a guest of Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian, Kiyuma said
the two countries have established friendly and cooperative
relations in a wide range of areas since the conclusion of the
Sino-Japanese treaty of peace and friendship 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said that an exchange of visits between defense ministers of
the two countries this year is of significance not only to
relations between Japan's Self-Defense Forces and the Chinese
People's Liberation Army but also to Sino-Japanese ties as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Defense Minister Chi visited Japan in February.
</P>
<P>
Kiyuma reiterated that Japan will continue to take the path of
peaceful development.
</P>
<P>
In response to questions after his speech, Kiyuma said that the
Japanese government fully recognizes the government of the
People's Republic of China as the sole legal government
representing China and understands and respects the fact that
Taiwan is an inalienable part of Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a bill adopted by Japan's cabinet on April 28
points to developments in areas surrounding Japan that have an
important influence on Japan's peace and security, but does not
point to a geographic concept in which any area would be included
or excluded.
</P>
<P>
On the Korean peninsula issue, he said that this should be
resolved basically by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) and the Republic of Korea (ROK) through consultations.
</P>
<P>
He said that Japan supports the four-party talks by the United
States, China, the DPRK and the ROK.
</P>
<P>
Kyuma's China visit began on May 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Allows Foreign Banks to Enter Interbank Call Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Some foreign banks operating in
China recently got the go-ahead to enter China's national
interbank call market.
</P>
<P>
With the approval of the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, eight foreign banks with the right to do Renminbi business
in the Pudong New Area in Shanghai now can participate in
interbank borrowing, bond trading and bond repurchasing through a
national trading and information network.
</P>
<P>
The eight banks include Industrial Bank of Japan, Daiichi
Kangyo Bank, Citibank, Standard Hong Kong and Shanghai Bank,
Charter Bank and Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
Since Pudong was opened to foreign banks in April of 1997 the
interbank activities in Renminbi have been performed through the
Shanghai Financing Center.
</P>
<P>
Chinese financial experts call the move a further step in
opening China's financial market.  
