<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Shipping Group to Set Up New Subsidiaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The China Yangtze Shipping (Group)
Corp., the country's largest inland-river shipping enterprise,
plans to set up five big subsidiaries this year specializing in
transportation of passengers, cargo, oil, containers and in
tourism.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Ministry of Communications said the
reorganization will intensify regional cooperation and increase
the group's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The companies will replace the four existing branches in the
cities of Shanghai, Wuhu, Wuhan and Chongqing. The branches have
similar industrial structures and duplication of navigation
routes, thus causing excessive internal cost, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze Shipping Group's transport volume has fallen
continuously in the past years to 12 million tons in 1997,
with two-thirds of its capacity unused because of the challenge
from railways, highways and air routes.
</P>
<P>
The reorganization plan calls for the group to form a
management pattern with shipping as the pillar and covering
tourism, industry, real estate, trade and finance early next
century.
</P>
<P>
At present, the group has 110,000 employees and more than 10
billion yuan in assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
