<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 08:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Willing to Accept Abu Dis as Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- In a surprising stance change,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has expressed his willingness to
accept Abu Dis on Jerusalem's eastern suburb as the capital of a
future Palestinian state, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The prestigious Hebrew daily Haaretz said in a front-page story
that Arafat made the statement in Ramallah during this weekend's
meeting with a U.S. delegation from the New York-based Council of
Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, the idea of Abu Dis, which belonged to Al Qods
(Jerusalem) under Jordanian control, is acceptable," he told the
American visitors when asked if an agreement could be reached on
the sensitive issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem problem is considered as one of the most sticking
points in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks as both of Israel
and the Palestinians insisted that the city should be the capital
of their own states.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo peace accords reached in 1993 between the
Palestinians and Israelis, the issue should be resolved in
the final-status talks between the two sides. Jerusalem is not
only a holy city for Jews, but also for Muslims and Christians.
</P>
<P>
Arafat pointed out that he viewed understandings between the
two sides in the 1996 as realistic foundations for a final
settlement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan formulated by Israel's Labor lawmaker
Yossi Beilin and Arafat's deputy Abu Mazen on the eve of the last
Israeli general elections in 1996, most settlements under Israeli
control will remain, whereas settlers living in highly populated
Palestinian areas could live in the Palestinian state or move to
Israeli territories.
</P>
<P>
The plan also envisioned that the Jordan Valley would remain
under Israeli control for seven years from the signing of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Arafat's remarks has surprised both of the
American visitors and the Israeli officials who were especially
excited by the Abu Dis solution.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation met with Beilin Monday to brief him on
Arafat's surprising positions regarding the future of Jerusalem,
the principle of territorial compromise and the establishment of a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said that Arafat's remarks proved how attainable peace
was and that the current Likud government would be missing a
huge opportunity if the Oslo process fell apart.
</P>
<P>
He urged responsible persons in the government and the
coalition not to lend a hand to the head-on collision to
which Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is leading, when it is
clear that a permanent peace can be reached and can save the
whole nation.
</P>
<P>
Members of the American delegation included Lester Crown,
President of General Dynamics Corporation, Patrick Lang, a former
director of human intelligence collection for the U.S. government,
Robert Lifton and a former President of the American Jewish Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
