<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macadamia Yield Hits New High in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Macadamia yield in Kenya has more
than doubled over the past six years and hit new high last year,
thanks to the liberalization of the industry, according to a
local report available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 6,800 tons of wet in-shell nuts were produced in
1997, up by 38 percent over 1996. Exports were a record 918 tons
of processed kernel worth 412 million Shillings (6.9 million U.S.
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The hike is attributed to favorable weather conditions toward
the end of 1996, high farmer morale, good prices and the fast
increasing number of macadamia nut trees across the east African
country, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, the report only predicted a marginal increase in
macadamia yield of two percent this year due to heavy El Nino
rains between October, 1997 and March this year.
</P>
<P>
The rains have led to substantial abortion of flowers in the
fields and this is likely to affect overall production in most
areas.
</P>
<P>
Macadamia tree growing is mainly a small holder farmer
activity mainly in Eastern, Central and recently in Western and
Rift Valley provinces of the country. Most farmers inter-crop
macadamia trees with coffee or other crops.
</P>
<P>
As the export demand has remained high for years, the price
for a seedling in the country went up to 100 Shillings (1.7
Dollars) last year from 60 Shillings (about one Dollar) in the
previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 08:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Raises Oil Price to Increase Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Supreme Petroleum
Council has decided to raise domestic fuel prices by 40-50
percent as part of the measures to curb dropped income arising from
world oil price fall, Arab Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The prices of regular and premium petrol now available in
Kuwaiti market will be separately raised to 60 and 70 fils (about
0.198 and 0.231 U.S. dollars) per liter from the current 40 and 50
fils (about 0.132 and 0.165 dollars), the paper quoted Kuwaiti Oil
Minister Sheikh Saud Al-Sabah as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah said the planned increase, the first of its kind over
the past 15 years, was "necessary" to deal with the current
situation.
</P>
<P>
The rise is expected to go into effect four months from now
after it is approved by the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Due to the sluggish oil price in world markets, the
oil-depending Kuwait, which hosts 10 percent of the world proven
oil reserves and exports 3.5 percent of the world oil demand, is
estimated to see a 6.6 billion dollars of budget deficit in its
1998-99 fiscal year (July 1 to June 30), the highest since the
Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah warned last month that Kuwait could face an "economic
catastrophe" if Kuwait's crude remained at 10.5 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
And Kuwaiti Cabinet last month asked its economic committee to
search for new sources of income in response to the oil price
fall.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister Nasser Abdullah Al-Roudhan said
"we are talking about a package of measures linked to both
expenditures and revenues," including the planned domestic fuel
price hike.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad
Al-Jaber Al-Sabah said Monday that Kuwait would support a further
OPEC oil output cut to help boost world oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
