<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Urges OAU to Be Resolute in Ending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President and current
Chairman of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), Robert
Mugabe has urged the organization to be resolute in ending
conflicts for economic prosperity on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Briefing journalists at the Harare international airport
shortly before the departure of Burkina Faso's President Blaise
Campaore Monday, Mugabe said it was the wish of the OAU to have
established an African economic community by 2030, but its
efforts were being frustrated by political instability in some
countries, The Herald reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said lack of adequate financial resources was also
hindering the continental body from establishing the economic
block aimed at achieving economic progress.
</P>
<P>
He added there are still some areas of conflict in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In Sierra Leone, rebels are still fighting the legitimate
government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
There is turmoil in Comoros, while the Great Lakes region is
also not yet totally stable.
</P>
<P>
In Angola the situation is also unpredictable, as the peace
process in that country is moving at a snail's pace. The 1994
Lusaka Peace Protocol has not yet been fully implemented, and
there are still reports of skirmishes between the government
troops and former rebel guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
"With all these conflicts, it's difficult to have a smooth
economic program. The OAU has to be resolute and grapple with all
these conflicts," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
In view of all these problems, the heads of state and
government were expected to pay particular attention in the areas
of conflict resolution, among other issues, during the next OAU
summit to be held in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, during the first
week of June, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same occasion, Compaore said there was need to
consolidate what had so far been achieved by ensuring stability
on the continent.
</P>
<P>
He arrived in Harare Sunday on a two-day working visit to
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders held private talks. During the meeting Mugabe
briefed Compaore on OAU's peace efforts, and the current
situation on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe will hand over the chairmanship of the OAU to Compaore
at next month's OAU heads of state and government summit in
Burkina Faso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
