<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Urge Preserving Bengal Tigers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Experts have called for preserving
Bengal tigers which they said are on the brink of extinction, The
New Nation daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bengal tigers live in Bangladesh's southeast district of Kulna
where there is the largest mangrove forest in the world -- the
Sundarbans.
</P>
<P>
A census conducted by the Forest Department in 1973 showed that
there were 350-400 Bengal tigers in Bangladesh then, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
But the number of Bengal tigers has being gradually decreasing
because a tiger preservation project initiated 24 years ago has
failed to provide a safe sanctuary for the tigers.
</P>
<P>
Now there are only 300 Bengal tigers, the newspaper said,
quoting an official of the Forest Department.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes hungry male tigers eat up cubs, some tigers are
killed when they enter the adjacent townships or villages, and
some by poachers who want the skin, teeth and nail, and all these
may be the main causes of the reduction of tigers, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, in deep forest there is no sweet water which is
necessary for the tiger, and there are also no treatment
facilities for the sick ones.
</P>
<P>
Project plans had been prepared for four times in the country,
but all yielded no result.
</P>
<P>
The latest plan was prepared in fiscal 1994-95 with an
involvement of 71.1 million taka (about 1.76 million U.S.
dollars), and the World Wildlife Preservation Fund offered to
provide financial support for the project. But the project could
not start due to alleged bureaucratic bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
Experts called on departments concerned to take effective
measures immediately to save the Bengal tigers from further wane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
