<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Map Records of Japanese Migration to Manchuria Open to Public (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A Japan-published map detailing
Japanese migration to northeast China, formerly known as
Manchuria, has recently been shown to the public in Harbin,
capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The map, so far the sole first-hand evidence found of Japanese
invasion and migration to China, has just been rated as a
class-one state cultural relic.
</P>
<P>
Sun Fenglai, a collector of antiques, accidentally found the
map -- 74 centimeters long and 54 centimeters wide -- at a salvage
station in December of 1995. He bought the map and donated it to
the Northeast China Martyrs' Museum.
</P>
<P>
Printed with red, black and pale green offset plates and still
completely intact, the map clearly shows 125 migration areas,
scattered primarily in northeast China's Heilongjiang and Jilin
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Most of those migration areas are located in fertile and
rich-resource areas, the map shows.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the original land owners were driven out of their
homes by force, which is in sharp contrast to Japanese claims that
Japanese civilians were opening up wasteland in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The Mirong Village, now called Mengjiagang Village of Yilan
County, could be spotted on the map. The bloody Tulongshan Riot
took place here when Chinese peasants resisted Japanese migrants
who crossed the straits to grab their land. Unarmed peasants were
killed in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
Japanese migrants grabbed a total of 1.52 million hectares of
fertile land from native Chinese and left countless Chinese
civilians homeless to become refugees or subjected to laboring for
the Japanese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Map Records of Japanese Migration to Manchuria Open to Public (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experts here say that during the period from the Sino-Japanese
War of 1894-1895 to September 18, 1931 when Japan invaded
northeast China, Japan's governments never ceased to organize
migrations to northeast China in an effort to achieve its goal of
long-term occupation of China. However, it officially began to
adopt migration as a state policy only after September 18, 1931.
</P>
<P>
At that time the Japanese government planned to send one
million households into China within 20 years. The whole
operation, scheduled to be carried out in four phases, focused
primarily on the immigration of farmers, in addition to migrants
dealing with fisheries, mineral resources and forestry.
</P>
<P>
The left bottom corner of the map shows clearly: printed by
Japanese migration department in 1939, the year when Japanese
migration to northeast China climbed to its peak.
</P>
<P>
In the right bottom corner of the map, notes indicate that
different signs represented different migration areas, including
Youth Volunteers, Special Training Stations, Patroling Police
Villagers and so on, which is also contradictory to Japanese
claims that the migrants were all unarmed civilians.
</P>
<P>
Experts here indicate that those migrants were fully armed. In
addition to conducting production activities, the migrants also
conducted military training.
</P>
<P>
In the later periods of the War of Resistance Against Japan
(1937-1945), those migration areas had become major
soldier-suppliers, and by the time when the war ended there were
hardly any Japanese adults left in those migration areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Increases Control over Medicine Production, Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has initiated a
three-to-five-year program to improve the quality of medicines in
the urban and rural markets, according to an official of the
Municipal Bureau of Health.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to supervise the development, production,
usage, marketing, advertising and pricing of medicines.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that more than 90 percent of Beijing-made
medicine is up to national standards.
</P>
<P>
The health official said a comprehensive supervision system
will be in place by 2000, and more quality supervisors will be
employed.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 16 percent of the medicines sold in the capital is
made in Beijing. Related departments will offer preferential
policies to the city's pharmaceutical enterprises to increase the
varieties of medicine to 1,500 and develop new products, said the
official.  
</P>
