<HEADLINE> Northwest China Autonomous Region Developing Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- An official from Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region in northwest China said that tourism will be
given more emphasis this year.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhenyuan, director of the region's tourism bureau, said
that Ningxia attracted more than 4,000 overseas tourists in 1997,
with tourism revenue of 1.3 million U.S. dollars, up 8.3 percent
and 17 percent, respectively, from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia also attracted 1.57 million domestic tourists, with
revenue exceeding 260 million yuan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
As the only Hui autonomous region in China, Ningxia is
distinguished by its combination of deserts and lakes. Tourists
are also attracted by its ancient Yellow River culture, relics and
ethnic tradition.
</P>
<P>
Travel experts say the region has great tourism
potentialities. The region has invested more than 3 million yuan
to build the mausoleum of Emperor Xixia, an ancient emperor in the
Ningxia area. Ningxia will also prepare several tourism routes
like the ancient Xixia empire, desert scenery, and exploration of
the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
By year 2000 Ningxia is expected to draw 10,000 overseas
tourists annually, with 2 million U.S. dollars of tourism
revenue. It will receive two million domestic tourists, with
tourism revenue exceeding 500 million yuan. By 2002, the whole
region will get more than one billion yuan in annual tourism
revenue, covering 3 percent of the region's gross domestic
product, experts predict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
