<HEADLINE> Northeastern Chinese Provinces Trying To Help Unemployed People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Governor Zhang Guoguang of
northeast China's Liaoning Province recently signed letters of
responsibility with the mayors of 14 local cities and assigned
them goals of helping unemployed people find jobs.
</P>
<P>
The mayors' goal is to help 1.2 million people who has lost
their jobs at state-owned or collectively-owned enterprises find
jobs within three years, local sources say.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is China's oldest industrial base and has a tenth of
the country's state-owned large and medium-sized enterprises. Many
people lost their jobs when companies started laying off workers
to improve efficiency, and there are now more than two million of
them, accounting for a sixth of China's unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Local governments at the provincial or lower levels have
established an employment service network that provides
registration, job training and placement, and social
security. Since 1994, It has helped more than a million laid-off
workers find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Cities have tried other ways to help workers with special
difficulties through other forms of security, pensions, and
welfare, and more effective old age, medical care, and accident
coverage.
</P>
<P>
In Changchun, the capital of Jilin Province, which is close to
Liaoning, the city government department has assigned 118 workers
to form eight employment service groups to be responsible for job
placement, information, funds, and job training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
