<HEADLINE> China To Hold International Conference on Iron, Steel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese metallurgical officials will
announce China's investment and development plans for 2010
concerning major steel products, especially the sheet steel
production, at an international conference on the iron and steel
industry.
</P>
<P>
The China Iron and Steel Conference 1998 will be held June
10-11. It will focus on flat rolled steel products, according to
Lu Xiaoming, editor in chief of China Metals, an authoritative
newsletter for the industry.
</P>
<P>
Officials in charge of development planning with the State
Administration of Metallurgical Industry "will unveil the most
interesting findings of their recent market surveys on priority
steel products," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the administration of the recently defunct Ministry
of Metallurgical Industry conducted a series of studies on market
demand, production capacities, product quality, and imports and
exports of sheet products for auto manufacturing, ship building,
household electrical appliances, pipelines and other uses.
</P>
<P>
Future policies and planning will be based on the survey
results, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
The conference is being co-sponsored by the recently founded
administration and China Metals.
</P>
<P>
According to an official in charge of organizing the
conference, major officials of the administration will attend the
event along with representatives from major iron and steel
businesses of such countries as China, Germany, Japan, Britain and
the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Participants will also discuss the latest global developments
in plate steel production, and China's technology introduction and
upgrades in this area.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, of the 12 million tons of China's annual
steel imports, two-thirds are flat steel products.
</P>
<P>
This category accounts for 80 percent of the products in short
supply. And, currently, technology-intensive and high value-added
flat products merely control half of the domestic market on
average.  
</P>
