<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elected Village leaders Work in Democratic Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 5 (Xinhua) -- "Recently the villagers' congress
passed a bill to repair the roads, and all the villagers have
tried their best to support the project," said Zheng Songqian,
Head of Ximingyi Village in Yanling County, in central China's
Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
"It is much easier for the village leaders who have been
elected by the villagers themselves to work with the help and
participation of village representatives," he said. "In the past,
villagers often got angry with their leaders who managed village
affairs in the old, administrative way."
</P>
<P>
Democracy also helps in supervising the leaders, he said. Two
years ago, a village leader was ousted by the villagers' congress
because of his incompetence.
</P>
<P>
Zheng was elected village head in 1994 after he defeated 11
other candidates in three rounds of voting by 980 adult voters.
</P>
<P>
The village, with more than 370 households, has more than 30
congress delegates, namely one from every 10 families. The
congress meets five-to-six times a year. The congressmen look over
all the work of the village administration.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1970s, when China began its reforms first in
rural areas and then in cities, farmers have gained their own
decision-making rights, instead of the former practice of letting
the people's communes decide everything.
</P>
<P>
In November of 1987, China issued the law on organization of
village committees. Henan Province began to experiment with the
democratic election of village leaders in 1988. By the end of
1994, all 48,000 villages in the province had held democratic
elections in line with the law.
</P>
<P>
"Democratic administration is new to all of us, and we have
much to learn," local village leaders agreed. Many of them have
taken training of various kinds. Some have a college diploma.
</P>
<P>
Local governments at all levels have encouraged experimental
democracy in local villages. Village leaders have been asked to
open up their administrative activities to the villagers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
