<HEADLINE> Southwestern China's Yunnan Province Looking For Overseas Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- China's Yunnan Province is hoping to
have 36 million tourists annually by the year 2002, with 1.3
million coming from overseas.
</P>
<P>
That means an increase of 60 percent from now. Total earnings
from tourism will exceed 20 billion yuan a year. The province had
20 million tourists in 1997, more than 800,000 of them from
overseas, and did 260 million U.S. dollars worth of overseas
tourism, putting it in seventh place in China in terms of overseas
tourists and related earnings.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan is China's window on Southeast Asia, with a 4,000-km
border with Vietnam, Laos and Myanmar. In recent years, one third
of its overseas tourists have come from Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The governor of the province, Li Jiating, said recently that
they need to target tourist sources in Europe, North America and
Japan to meet this goal, while keeping the tourist market in
Southeast Asia and expanding border tourism.
</P>
<P>
He says that they will start new tourist agencies in the United
States, Japan, Thailand and Hong Kong, and get agencies from
Europe, North America, Japan and Thailand to open joint ventures
in Yunnan, and encourage international hotel groups to join with
local hotels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
