<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Students Denied Service in U.S. Restaurant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Black sixth-graders on a field
trip to Disney World were denied service at a Denny's restaurant
in Florida, the United States, school officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
That is the latest in a series of complaints against the chain
that settled a 46 million dollar discrimination lawsuit in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The students from Baltimore's Ashburton Elementary-Middle
School and their chaperones entered the Denny's restaurant in
Ocoee, Florida, Thursday night and were not greeted or seated,
said school officials.
</P>
<P>
After seating themselves, the students waited 20 minutes before
some received menus and left an hour later without being served.
Meanwhile, white customers who entered later were served, said
school officials, who said they planned to file a complaint with
the company.
</P>
<P>
"The way we were greeted shows, actually entering the
restaurant, we were not welcomed," the Associated Press quoted
chaperone Peggy Brown as saying.
</P>
<P>
The incident will be investigated, said Ray Hood-Phillips,
chief diversity officer for Denny's, a post created following the
1994 settlement.
</P>
<P>
"If we find that discrimination has occurred, it doesn't matter
if it's a company store or a franchise unit, we take swift
action," Hood-Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
"Employees are fired if they're found to discriminate, and if
it's a franchise, we take the franchise away."
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit settled in 1994 was brought by black Secret Service
agents who said they were denied service.
</P>
<P>
In January, several Florida corrections officers filed a
discrimination complaint against Denny's, saying they were turned
away twice from one restaurant.
</P>
<P>
As part of an agreement with the Justice Department, the
restaurant chain agreed to retrain employees, feature minorities
in its ads and hire an outside lawyer to monitor compliance.
</P>
<P>
The South Carolina-based chain has 891 company-owned and 716
franchised restaurants nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
