<HEADLINE> British Group Eyes Thai Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The British Airports Authority (BAA)
has asked for approval from Thailand's Transport and Communication
Ministry to manage the operation of Phuket airport in the south,
the Bangkok Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Transport and Communication Minister Suthep Thueksuban said BAA
representatives had presented a detailed plan to run Phuket
airport so that it would attract more international airlines.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been worked out over the past 18 months and
focuses on the improvement of the shuttle service between the
airport and other areas of Phuket island.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, an airport privatization study was
conducted by the ministry, which suggested that the three regional
airports in Phuket, Chiang mai in the north and Hat Yai in the
south, be privatized as single package.
</P>
<P>
BAA said it was flexible over the size of its stake in the Thai
airport, but stressed it wanted sole management authority.
</P>
<P>
However, BAA was told that it had to bid for the right to run a
Thai airport since several foreign parties from Europe and America
had also expressed an interest.
</P>
<P>
The Transport and Communication Ministry has yet to propose its
airport privatization plan to the cabinet for approval and will
set up a bidding contest to select a private contractor
afterwards, the minister said. 
</P>
