<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, May 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The first annual inflation rate in March for the 11
Euro founding countries was 1.2 percent, according to the European
Commission's statistical bureau Monday.
</P>
<P>
A year earlier, the rate was 1.5 percent for Belgium, Germany,
France, Spain, Italy, Ireland, the Netherlands, Portugal, Austria,
Finland and Luxembourg. (Eurostat-Euro-Inflation Rate)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean exports to southeast Asian countries
plummeted by 31.2 percent to 3.47 billion U.S. dollars in the
first quarter of this year, the Korea International Trade
Association said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Indonesia plunged by 51 percent while those to
Thailand, Malaysia and Singapore fell by 46.5 percent, 36.7
percent and 30.8 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The trade association attributed the export decline to the
ongoing financial crisis in South Korea and to local financial
institutions' unwillingness to deal with export bills to and from
the region. (SKorea-Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam plans to expand the export-oriented
rice-growing area to one million hectares, mainly in the four
major rice-growing provinces in the southern Mekong Delta, the
Vietnam news reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
About 5.9 million tons of quality rice will be produced in the
area, of which 3-3.5 million tons are for
export. (Vietnam-Rice-Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The foreign direct investment has increased 11
percent during 1996 in Central American countries, an economic
report released on Monday said.
</P>
<P>
The report on foreign investment in Latin America and the
Caribbean, issued by the Economical Commission for Latin America
and the Caribbean, said the increase is mainly due to flow of more
foreign direct investment into Panama, Honduras and Nicaragua.
(Central America-Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Swedish Finance Minister Erik Asbrink clarified on
Monday that there is no fixed timetable for Sweden to join
European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
The minister said this after comments he made over the weekend
were interpreted as meaning that Sweden could join the EMU before
the introduction of euro. (Sweden-EMU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Businessmen from Mexico and Cuba signed an
agreement Monday on establishing a joint venture, the first of its
kind between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, "Pesca Caribe," will absorb an investment of
more than three million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company will engage in fishing species such as lobster and
crawfish in the Caribbean waters and then selling them to the two
countries' tourist areas. (Mexico-Cuba-Agreement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Latin America and the Caribbean received a
record high amount of foreign investment in 1997 despite the
effects of financial crises in Mexico and one in Asia, a
U.N. organization said in a report on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Direct foreign investments (DFI) in the region hit 50 billion
U.S. dollars last year, with Brazil, Mexico, Argentina and Chile
topping the list of favored DFI receivers, said the report issued
by the Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean
(ECLAC).
</P>
<P>
The United States was the largest foreign investor in the
region, followed by the European Union. (Latin America-Foreign
Capital) 
</P>
