<HEADLINE> Drug Abuse By Youngsters Rampant in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Drug abuse among youngsters in
Thailand shows no sign of abating as the number of drug cases
makes up the highest percentage in criminal cases concerning
youth, The Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Vicha Mahakhun, deputy chief justice of the
Central Juvenile and Family Court (CJFC), 43.5 percent of the drug
cases tried by the court last year were committed by youth.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by the court, most children
addicted to drugs came from broken families and they lived with
friends.
</P>
<P>
Most of the child addicts' fathers were addicted to alcohol or
had drug-addicted siblings, the survey revealed.
</P>
<P>
Most of the young addicts said they took to drugs initially out
of novelty. The second most popular reason for drug addiction was
the need to endure longer hours of work, while the third most
cited reason was persuasion by friends and problems with parents.
</P>
<P>
Most young addicts were laborers, and the rest included the
unemployed, the survey showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
