<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb President Refutes Accusation by American Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 4 (Xinhua)-- Bosnian Serb President Biljana
Plavsic Monday rejected as completely groundless an accusation by
an American military envoy that the army of the Republic of Srpska
has been threatening the peace process in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Dzejms Pardj, American military envoy to the
Balkan region, Plavsic demanded that he clarify whether he was
making the statement on behalf of the U.S. government or he was
just expressing his personal views, the Tanjug news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Pardj had asserted that the threat could be eliminated only if
Bosnian Serb Prime Minister Milorad Dodik reorganized the army
whereby all officers participating in Bosnia's civil war under
General Manojl Milovanovic would be removed, Plavsic said.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serb president said the government of Srpska and
its army had been highly cooperative and had fully implemented the
Dayton Peace Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The president said Pardj did not mention how the Bosnian Serb
army threatened the peace process in Bosnia. It is actually the
U.S. envoy's statement that has posed a threat to the peace
atmosphere in the region, she said.
</P>
<P>
She warned at the end of the letter that the current paramount
threat to the peace process in Bosnia-Herzegovina was the
discriminative attitudes toward the various parties in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
