<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millions of American Children Still Live in Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The percentage of Southern
children living in poverty in the United States is about the same
as it was in 1969, regardless of robust economies in most southern
states, the Children's Defense Fund said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Equally disturbing is the fact that the rest of the nation is
catching up with the South," The Associated Press quoted Marian
Wright Edelman, president of the Washington-based nonprofit child
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the western U.S. states matched the southern states in
the percentage of poor children -- 22.9 percent -- the first time
another region equaled the south in child poverty, said a report
issued by the group at a two-day meeting in Memphis, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
The defense fund placed the poverty line at 12,516 dollars for
a family of three and 16,036 dollars for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
The organization said that in 1996, 5.5 million children living
in the 16-state southern area, including Washington, D.C., were
poor, and that 2.6 million lived in extreme poverty, with incomes
of about 120 U.S. dollars a week for a family of three.
</P>
<P>
In 1969, 22.3 percent of children in families living in the
south were poor. In 1996, 22.9 percent of all Southern children --
including those in foster care, living on their own, or with a
non-related adult -- were living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
The midwest had the lowest percentage of impoverished children
among the four regions, 11.5 percent, followed by the northeast
with 19.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, 20.5 percent of children, or almost 14.5 million,
were classified as poor in 1996. That's up from 14 percent in
1969, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The defense fund and other child advocacy groups are gearing up
for a new push for more federal and state help to reduce child
poverty. They want a commitment from Congress for 20 billion
dollars in the next five years for early childhood education,
child care and other programs.
</P>
<P>
The defense fund found that 84 of the 100 counties with the
highest percentage of children living in poverty were in the
South. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
