<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armenia Decides to Return Art Treasures to Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Armenian President Robert Kocharyan
signed a decree on Monday to return all the cultural and art
treasures Armenia took from Germany after World War II.
</P>
<P>
A presidential spokesman told the Itar-Tass news agency that
Kocharyan made the decision in accordance with a bilateral
cultural agreement between Armenia and Germany and an Armenian law
regulating the flow of cultural treasures.
</P>
<P>
He said the presidential decree represents an honorable
execution of relevant resolutions of the U.N. General Assembly,
which require the return of illegally obtained cultural treasures.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the return of cultural and art treasures has been
plaguing relations between Germany and some countries of the
former Soviet Union, especially Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree not long ago to
return many of the cultural and art treasures Russia took from
Germany. But the decree was vetoed by both the State Duma (the
lower house of parliament) and the Constitutional Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
