<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand May Fail to Reach Export Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is unlikely to achieve this
year's export target of 62.6 billion U.S. dollars, or a 7.1
percent increase from last year, if the decline shown in the first
quarter continues, the Bangkok Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted government house spokesman Akapol
Sorasuchart as saying that a worrisome decline in first quarter
exports has underlined the need to resolve the tight liquidity in
the domestic market and ensure the continued stability of the
baht.
</P>
<P>
Exports in U.S. dollar term for the first quarter of this year
fell by 2.8 percent to 13.65 billion dollars compared to the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the decline is believed to be importers'
demand for dollar price cuts after the baht's devaluation, Akapol
said.
</P>
<P>
There had also been a sharp drop in imports of capital goods,
raw materials and semi-finished products -- essential items for
producing goods for export, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This suggested that manufacturers do not have the funds to
purchase the goods they need, he added.
</P>
<P>
First quarter imports in terms of U.S. dollar fell by 38.6
percent from the same period last year as a result of the
liquidity crunch, high interest rates and the baht's instability.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures from the Business Economics Department
showed that imports of capital goods in the first two months of
this year fell by 34.2 percent, while imports of raw materials
dropped by 42.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Akapol said if imports of these essential goods continued to
decline, it would hurt exports in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said government agencies had been trying to solve problems
such as refunds on value-added tax and raw material import tax,
and registration of goods for export.
</P>
<P>
However, liquidity and the exchange rate volatility are the
most urgent issues to be tackled, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
