<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs from Latin American Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic news
briefs from Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Argentine government plans to collect more
than 30 billion U.S. dollars in foreign investments within the
next six years.
</P>
<P>
The money will be allocated for the most part to the province
of Buenos Aires, with 18 billion dollars going into the
construction sector and 12 billion dollars to the service area.
</P>
<P>
The United States is Argentina's number one foreign investor
with almost 12 billion dollars, followed by Spain with 8.8 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- A total of 38,737 new vehicles were sold during the
first quarter of the year in Chile, up 1.1 percent from the same
period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the National Automobile Industry of Chile show
that the U.S. Chevrolet occupied 17.3 percent of the market with a
sale of 2,199 units.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Hyundai came in second with 1,659 units,
occupying 13.1 percent of the market, followed by Japan's Suzuki,
with 1,177 units and an 8.3 percent participation.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Association of the Central American and the
Caribbean Stock Exchange (BOLCECA) will establish a regional stock
exchange within the following 10 months.
</P>
<P>
A computerized system will be set up there to help make
transactions between other separate central American stock
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The BOLCECA said the project is designed to trigger transaction
mechanisms for the stock exchange at a regional level.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The volume of Uruguay's stock exchange market
transaction totaled 326.2 million dollars in April this year, up
97.1 percent from the previous month and 200 percent from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Montevideo Stock Exchange represented 16.3 percent of the
total volume, while the Electronic Stock Exchange registered 83.7
percent with 273.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter this year, stock exchange transactions
in Uruguay reached 1.5 billion dollars, representing a 350 percent
increase from that in 1997.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The export of shoes in Brazil amounted to 345
million dollars in the first quarter of this year, down 12 percent
from the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
During the January-April period, shoe exports totaled 41.1
million pairs, a decrease of 5.4 percent compared with the same
period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain are the two major markets for
Brazil's shoes.
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia has tripled the volume of its
carbon export to the international market in the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian Company of Carbon said that exports of the
mineral went from 9.6 million tons to 27.4 millions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Europe, the major market for Colombia's carbon, bought 73
percent of the country's sales last year, while American countries
acquired 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico settled 12.79 billion dollars of its
145.33 billion-dollar external debt in 1997, said the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the external debt of the country's public
sector was 83 billion dollars, and the private sector's debt was
62.33 billion dollars, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
