<HEADLINE> Foreign Investments in Latin America Hit Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Latin America and the Caribbean
received a record high amount of foreign investment in 1997
despite the effects of financial crises in Mexico and one in Asia,
a U.N. organization said in a report on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Direct foreign investments (DFI) in the region hit 50 billion
U.S. dollars last year, with Brazil, Mexico, Argentina and Chile
topping the list of favored DFI receivers, said the report issued
by the Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean
(ECLAC).
</P>
<P>
The United States was the largest foreign investor in the
region, followed by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Zapata, chief of ECLAC's international trade unit, said
in a press release here that countries in Latin America and the
Caribbean are making significant progress towards economic
integration, offsetting the negative impact of domestic problems
and financial crises in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
This will encourage future DFI flows into the region, he
predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
