<HEADLINE> Forest Fire Haze Affects Residents in South Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Residents, especially children in
two districts of Thailand's southernmost province of Narathiwat
have been seriously affected by the haze from a fire at the
adjacent Phru Toh Daeng Peat swamp forest, a press report said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fire has spread from the edge of the forest to the heart of
the swamp which is sensitive ecologically because the area
contains a number of endangered tree species unique only to the
locality.
</P>
<P>
Forestry officials estimated that as much as 25,000 rai (4,000
hectares) of forest had been burnt.
</P>
<P>
Decha Kasemsap, the manager of a school near the swamp area,
was quoted as saying that many of his students had been absent
from school since last Thursday because of the haze. Some
developed respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
"The school has to spare three teachers to take care of the
children who suffer from the haze while at school. We have
requested filtering masks from the provincial health office," he
said. 
</P>
