<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Fund System Being Tried In Chinese City's Industrial Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, May 5 (Xinhua) -- After a year of experiment, a
Sino-Singaporean public fund program being tried in an industrial
park in the city of Suzhou has shown itself to be practical,
according to Wu Wai Mun, the deputy director of Singapore's
Central Public Fund (CPF) Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's CPF is a successful social welfare system that
calls for employee welfare like housing, medicare, retirement
pensions, and unemployment benefits in institutions and
corporations to be independent of government pensions. Employers
pay into a fund based on 66 percent of the employees' monthly
salary that is transferred to a bank account every month.
</P>
<P>
It is being used in 107 companies in the park, with 5,600
employees and has accumulated 67 million yuan, 4.7 million yuan of
which is used for medical, unemployment and housing expenses, Wu
explains.
</P>
<P>
The majority of overseas investors in the park believe the
system helps keep labor costs down because the fund covers
everything with one lump sum and means that their companies are no
longer burdened with a range of welfare expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Alan J. Ridley, chairman of the U.K.'s Visuvius Co., says,
"This comprehensive social welfare undertaking is common in my
home country. We are glad to see the park has implemented the same
practice."
</P>
<P>
The public fund is also attractive to employees because it
provides a long-term solution to all their fundamental social
welfare problems.
</P>
<P>
The CPF system is known as one of the most successful practices
in Singapore's fast-moving economy and has helped 80 percent of
its people purchase their own houses.
</P>
<P>
The Suzhou Industrial Park has been borrowing from Singapore's
experience in other ways as well, such as construction,
environmental protection, and development plans, since it was set
up in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
