<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Price Hikes Expected to Fuel Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A rise in the prices of fuel oil and
electricity in Indonesia will push up inflation in May and June by
10 percent respectively, bringing this year's accumulative
inflation rate to more than 50 percent, an economist predicted.
</P>
<P>
The government said on Monday the prices of seven kinds of fuel
oil would increase by 25 to 71 percent starting Tuesday and that
of electricity by 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mari Elka Pangestu, executive director of the Center for
Strategic and International Studies (CSIS), said the oil price
hikes would be followed by an increase in transportation fares and
prices of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
She said the price increases were a bitter pill the government
has to take, but it should be followed by increased efficiency and
transparency in all policies.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's inflation rate in the first three months of this
year was more than 25 percent, according to the Central Statistics
Agency. 
</P>
