<HEADLINE> German Leader Promises New Drive for Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 4 (Xinhua) -- German Social Democrat leader Gerhard
Schroeder said here Monday he would initiate a radical shift in
employment policy while keeping the current foreign policy if he
becomes Germany's chancellor after September elections.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a press conference after meeting with
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini.
</P>
<P>
"There won't be changes of principle in German foreign policy,
even with a new government" said Schroeder, but on employment his
party would take a different line from present Chancellor Helmut
Kohl.
</P>
<P>
"In our view, European policy in this sector should not
substitute national policies, but complement them," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier meeting, Italian Left Democrats leader Massimo
D'Alema and Schroeder agreed that unemployment should now be the
main priority for the 11 countries in the euro area.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said that if he wins the elections his first concern
will be to push forward joint strategies to boost jobs and promote
a socially-sensitive Europe.
</P>
<P>
The problem of youth unemployment had been a key factor in
recent regional elections in Germany, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that if his Social democrat party wins the election, it
will be largely thanks to Kohl's failure in labor policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
