<HEADLINE> New Thai Central Bank Governor Nominated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda Monday nominated Chatumongol Sonakul, former
permanent secretary of the finance ministry, as the central bank
governor to replace outgoing Chaiyawat Wibulsawasdi.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said Chatumongol's nomination would be presented to the
cabinet meeting on Wednesday and that he was confident the
nomination would win approval, the Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said he had consulted Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai in
choosing Chatumongol and was confident his decision would increase
public confidence in the central bank.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Chaiyawat tendered his resignation with the finance
minister. His resignation becomes effective Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Two deputy governors, Jaroong Nookhwun and Siri Garnjaroendee,
also tendered their resignations.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat and Siri were identified by an investigation
commission led by former central bank governor Nukul Prachuabmoh
as among the seven people responsible for Bank of Thailand (BOT)'s
failed attempt to defend the baht against speculative attacks last
year.
</P>
<P>
The abortive attempt almost depleted the country's foreign
currency reserves which plunged from 36.6 billion U.S. dollars to
2.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The other five people on the "black list" of the commission are
former prime minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, former finance
minister Amnuay Viravan, former central bank governor Rerngchai
Marakanond, Bandhit Nijthavorn, director of BOT's Banking
Department and Paibul Kittisrikangwan, then head of BOT's analysis
and monetary market section.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chatumongol declared himself ready for the job.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post quoted him as saying that his priority would
be restructuring the central bank, particularly in terms of its
role in supervision and examination.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper described Chatumongol as a career civil servant
known for his direct manner.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol, born in 1942, received a BA degree from Cambridge
University of Britain and an MA degree from Harvard University of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
He worked in various departments of the finance ministry,
including the Fiscal Policy Department, the Revenue Department and
the Exercise Department.
</P>
<P>
He quit as permanent secretary of the finance ministry after
being transferred by the Chavalit administration to the prime
minister's office in July last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
