<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother's Day Stresses Support for Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- "Repaying mother's love and
assisting the poor" will be the theme for this year's Mother's Day
in China which falls on Sunday, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, Mother's Day has been designated by the
organizing committee of the nationwide "Happiness Program" as a
national day for promoting activities to help impoverished
mothers. The program is a charity project to help lift
impoverished mothers out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Data from the program organizing committee suggest there are
more than 10 million poverty-stricken mothers in the country, at
least 80 percent of them illiterate and in poor health.
</P>
<P>
The State Family Planning Commission has released a circular
calling on family planning commissions in each locality to support
the charity activity.
</P>
<P>
A publicity campaign and collections of donations will be
organized this week to inform more people of the charity project
and the living conditions of poor mothers.
</P>
<P>
The program was initiated in 1995 by the China Population Welfare
Foundation, the China National Family Planning Association and
Chinese Population News.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, it had received donations of over 48
million yuan (5.7 million US dollars) from communities and
individuals from all the social sectors.
</P>
<P>
A total of 32,000 poor mothers in 111 counties across the
country have been helped by the program in recent years. Some
6,000 have been lifted out of poverty and about 3,000 have become
better off, according to the newspaper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Keen to Develop Relations with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Foreign Minister Jose
Miguel Insulza said Monday his country holds its political and
economic relations with China in high esteem.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua before his official visit to China
on April 6-9, Insulza described relations between Chile and China
as "very good," adding that he hopes his visit will add greater
strength to the relationship.
</P>
<P>
In November 1995, Insulza accompanied Chilean President Eduardo
Frei on a visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister commended the policy of reform and opening
to the outside world adopted by the Chinese government since 1978,
saying that the policy has enabled China to achieve rapid economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Commenting that Chile was the first Latin American country to
recognize the Chinese government as the solely legitimate
representative of the Chinese people, Insulza stressed that his
country will always support the one-China policy and the peaceful
reunification of China.
</P>
<P>
China will play a stabilizing role in both regional and global
political affairs in the next century, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for economic cooperation, Insulza said that China is Chile's
second largest trade partner in Asia. Bilateral trade has
constantly increased, while large investments have also been made
between the two countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We entrust China with our greatest hope for developing
relations with Asia, and we believe that our trade policy with
China has great dynamism," the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
