<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Province Grants Health Certificates to Cows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May (Xinhua) -- Cow owners in northeast China's
Liaoning Province have to obtain a health license for their cows
before they sell fresh milk on the market.
</P>
<P>
This move has been taken by the Liaoning Provincial Animal
Husbandry Bureau to protect the people from the danger of drinking
milk infected with brucellosis and tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
The province launched a one-by-one health check of the 70,000
cows in Liaoning province last November and the last 20 cows found
infescted by brucellosis and tuberculosis have recently been
slaughtered and buried deep.
</P>
<P>
"Both the diseases can be easily caught by the people, and
infected cows can be a vehicle of such diseases," said Song
Shucai, deputy director of the Liaoning Provincial Animal
Husbandry Bureau.
</P>
<P>
He said that all the infected cows have been killed, while the
local government has provided subsidies to their owners since most
cows are privately owned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
