<HEADLINE> Cuba Wishes to Join Talks with European Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto
Robaina Gonzalez on Monday said that his country wishes to
accompany countries of the African, Caribbean and the Pacific
(ACP) forum in the negotiations for a new agreement with the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The Cuban minister is on a tour to Bridgetown, Barbados to
attend a ministerial meeting of the ACP forum held on May 4-6.
</P>
<P>
The ACP forum comprises of 71 countries, including 48 from
Africa, 15 from the Caribbean and eight from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez told reporters that the ACP has benefited from
cooperation with the 15-nation European Union through the Lome
convention which will expire in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
During the ACP meeting, the participants are expected to
discuss strategies to be adopted by the forum towards negotiations
with the EU on a new cooperation agreement.
</P>
<P>
The ACP ministerial meeting will be followed by a joint meeting
of representatives from the 71 ACP and 15 EU countries on May 7-8.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Bridgetown, Gonzalez is also expected to
have meetings with Barbados leaders including Prime Minister Owen
Arthur. 
</P>
</TEXT>
