<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Archbishop Warns Military to Be Neutral in Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Manila Archbishop Jaime Cardinal Sin
has warned the Philippine armed forces to "stay neutral" in next
week's elections, saying military intervention and any form of
cheating would be opposed with "people power," the Philippine Star
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the influential Roman Catholic archbishop as saying
that the Filipinos must accept the judgment of the electorate once
it is clear, "even if this judgment may differ from our personal
judgment."
</P>
<P>
Sin did not specify who he thought would try to steal the May
11 ballot, but spoke of a possible intervention by the armed
forces whose commander-in-chief is President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' preferred candidate, House Speaker Jose de Venecia, is
trailing the opposition candidate, Vice President Joseph Estrada,
in all popularity surveys.
</P>
<P>
"Intervention in the electoral process to gain victory for any
candidate by fraudulent means is a grave sin," he said, adding
that collusion by the military in any such intervention will be
opposed with "people power."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, former Philippine president Corazon Aquino also issued
the same warning.
</P>
<P>
"People power" is the synonym for the 1986 popular revolt in
which former president Ferdinand Marcos was toppled. Marcos was
accused of having stolen a snap presidential election against
Corazon Aquino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
