<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Become Taxi Drivers in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Some Tibetan farmers who used to ride
yaks as a means of transportation have never imagined that they
would be driving a taxi in the city of Lhasa, capital of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Because taxis are now in vogue in Lhasa, not only city
dwellers, but also farmers, are looking at this new way to make a
living.
</P>
<P>
Cedan, a farmer from the Lhasa suburbs, says, "Driving taxis is
really a good job. Farmers can make more money by driving taxis in
the city, and learn more at the same time."
</P>
<P>
Since the first taxi company was set up in Lhasa in 1994, the
number of taxis has increased from 10 to 970.
</P>
<P>
Farmers from the suburbs now account for half the taxi drivers
in Lhasa, where they make from 1,000 yuan to 3,000 yuan (360 US
dollars) a month, according to Losang Doje, director of the Lhasa
Taxi Administrative Office.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan passengers have begun choosing the taxi they want to
ride in, and Santana, a fairly spacious car, has become their
favorite, says Bai Ling, a taxi company manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
