<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Rebels Say Won't Disrupt Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippines' Muslim rebels said they
will not disrupt next week's national elections and most of them
will vote for candidates of their choice, the Manila Standard
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said Ghazali Jaafar, chief peace negotiator for the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), disputed press reports that
the MILF plans to disrupt the May 11 polls.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that about 1,000 armed men who claimed to be
MILF members surrounded a campaign rally last Saturday in
Mindanao, the southern Philippines, warning there will be
bloodshed if the elections were held as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar denied the men were MILF guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
"There is no truth that we have warned (the government) to
postpone the elections," he was quoted as saying. "In fact, with
the exception of the commanders, MILF guerrillas are free to
participate, campaign and vote."
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which has been holding peace talks with the
government since last year, is now the biggest rebel group still
fighting the government after the Moro National Liberation Front
signed a final peace agreement in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that more violence will take place during
the May 11 elections. At least 17 people have been killed in
election-related violence.
</P>
<P>
During the 1992 presidential elections, more than 100 people
were killed in election-related violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
