<HEADLINE> Mexico, Cuba to Establish Joint Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen from Mexico and Cuba
signed an agreement Monday on establishing a joint venture, the
first of its kind between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, "Pesca Caribe," will absorb an investment of
more than three million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company will engage in fishing several species such as
lobster and crawfish in the Caribbean waters and then selling them
to the two countries' tourist areas.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was held in Cancun, a scenic spot in
southeast Mexico, during the visit of Cuban Minister of Fishing
Orlando Rodriguez to the country.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Ambassador to Mexico Abelardo Curbelo said many Mexican
businessmen desire to invest in Cuba mainly in the fields of
mining, tourism, food industry, petroleum and fishing. 
