<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Northeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Jilin province in northeast China
is using various means to get foreign investment to promote its
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Jilin had used 5.1 billion US dollars worth
of foreign investment. Vice-Governor Wei Minxue says that this
meant an increase in the per-project investment from 656,000 US
dollars in 1992 to 1.23 million US dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment is used for infrastructural and industrial
projects and major projects are strongly supported by foreign
investment. About 40 percent of the funds for the 10 key projects
in the province during the 1991-95 period came from foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment was also used for state-owned enterprise
reforms. By last November, the province had approved 1,505 such
projects, involving 1.49 billion US dollars worth of foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies paid two billion yuan in taxes, or 13 percent
of the total tax revenues in Jilin in 1997, up 50 percent from
1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-backed companies have about 170,000 employees,
accounting for 1.4 percent of the total number of workers in
Jilin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
