<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McRae Survives Tyre Scare at Rally of Corsica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Colin McRae survived a big
scare in the Corsican Rally on Monday when he was disqualified
after his tyres were declared illegal but then reinstated on
appeal.
</P>
<P>
The British driver had taken an impressive lead in his Subaru
after the six stages on the first day.
</P>
<P>
But the rally stewards decided the treads on his car's tyres
were unusually worn and ruled they were thinner than the
regulations permitted.
</P>
<P>
Subaru appealed and the rally jury accepted the team's
explanations.
</P>
<P>
Subaru claimed that McRae's front right tyre had punctured at
the start of the second stage, putting more strain on the left
tyre.
</P>
<P>
The stewards accepted the Scot back into the rally because
of the "unusual circumstances".
</P>
<P>
As a result, McRae was reinstated at the top of the standings.
Frenchman Francois Delecour came second slower by 20.7 seconds
with McRae's Subaru teammate Piero Latti of Italy third, almost
three seconds further back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
