<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Preparing for Flood Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 5 (Xinhua) -- While northeast China is still
dealing with a serious drought, the city of Shanghai and
neighboring provinces are calling for help in flood control
activities.
</P>
<P>
The society has been urged to get ready early. The Minhang
District is setting aside 6.2 million yuan to repair a breach in
the 36-km Huangpu River Dike. The amount of funds from Fengxian
County for dikes and dams now amounts to 6.7 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say that, based on recent abnormal weather
conditions like windstorms, heavy late spring rains, and record
high water levels in the Yangtze River in the dry season, Shanghai
should prepare for serious flooding.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Qihua, head of the Shanghai water resources
bureau, Shanghai's facilities are not really ready for the fight
and that the city's 208-km bulwark for the urban area is only half
done.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that the city's fast growing economy cannot afford a
disaster.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Panel to Hold Hearing on Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 4 (Xinhua) -- A subcommittee of the U.S. Senate
is set to hold a hearing next month on a suspected increase in
abusive child labor in the United States, Senator Tom Harkin said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Senate Labor and Human Resources subcommittee on employment
scheduled a hearing on June 11, said Harkin, a senior Democrat on
the full committee.
</P>
<P>
"Child labor abuses are not confined to developing nations,"
Harkin said. "Most Americans would be shocked to see that some
children in this country are spending more time in factories and
fields than schools and playgrounds."
</P>
<P>
More than 290,000 children -- two-thirds of them 15 or younger
-- were employed illegally in the United States at some point in
1996, according to an Associated Press series published this
winter.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Labor Department found 36 working illegally in
Texas for nine companies. Some were as young as six years old,
Harkin's office said.
</P>
<P>
"It disturbs me that tens of thousands of American children are
being exploited by being forced to work illegally, and in some
cases in hazardous conditions," said Harkin, who requested the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
The senator said he planned to introduce legislation that would
increase minimum and maximum penalties for violators of child
labor laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980505.0309 </DOCNO>
