<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Disbursement of 989 Million US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) announced here Monday the approval of the release of the
next disbursement of about 989.4 million U.S. dollars equivalent
to Indonesia to help the country carry out reform program.
</P>
<P>
The payment, the second installment of a 10 billion dollar loan
approved last November, had been delayed from March while the two
sides renegotiated a new reform package under which Indonesia
introduced some reform measures.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Fischer, the Acting Managing Director of the
institution, issued a statement confirming the IMF Executive
Directors' approval of the payment.
</P>
<P>
Executive Directors noted that the revised program benefited
from a number of important prior actions by the Indonesian
authorities, including a strengthened monetary framework, the
statement said. Directors stressed the importance of sustained
implementation of the program for restoring confidence in the
Indonesian economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF approval would open the door to funding from bilateral
donors and other multilateral institutions. The IMF loan
constitutes part of a 40 billion dollar international rescue deal
for the trouble-ridden country.
</P>
<P>
The IMF three-year stand-by credit equivalent to 9.84 billion
dollars was approved on November 5, last year. Today's approval of
payment will bring total disbursements under the credit to about
3.96 billion dollars for Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
