<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blacks, Latinos Poorly Presented in Silicon Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Blacks and Latinos are largely
missing out on the Silicon Valley technology boom -- California's
most powerful economic engine, San Francisco Chronicle reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two minority groups, who make up 8 percent and 14 percent
of the San Francisco Bay Area labor force respectively, are the
fastest-growing segment of the state's population. But employment
records for 33 of the leading Silicon Valley firms show that their
Bay Area staffs are about 4 percent black and 7 percent Latino.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in these companies they work far more likely than
whites to hold factory, service and support jobs, and less likely
than whites to hold managerial and professional jobs.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper's research, education, laws and
discrimination are among the reasons for the lack of blacks and
Latinos in high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
In education, not enough blacks and Latinos are earning the
math and science degrees that prepare them for high-tech careers.
In addition, many Silicon Valley firms fail to seek out blacks and
Latinos at minority job fairs and college campuses with large
black and Latino populations. There are also virtually no
top-ranking blacks and Latinos in Silicon Valley to inspire and
mentor younger employees. Blacks and Latinos say racism exists in
high technology, as it does in other industries.
</P>
<P>
Under California's Affirmative Action laws, government
contractors -- including most large high-tech firms -- are
required to show they are making a good faith effort to recruit
minorities. But violators rarely pay fines.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the other side of the argument, the companies say it
is not the industry's fault that there are so few blacks and
Latinos qualified for professional high-tech jobs. Silicon Valley
considers itself a meritocracy, they say, where the color of a
person's skin doesn't matter as long as he can do the job.
</P>
<P>
They say that it is unfair to make corporations responsible for
education. In Silicon Valley, an engineering or computer science
degree is a ticket to full employment. But the supply is
shrinking. The number of math, computer science and engineering
bachelor's degrees earned by all U.S. students has slipped by
nearly one-fifth in the past decades and these degrees awarded to
blacks to Latinos were less than 11 percent of the total in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Chronicle argued that the lack of a math and science background
cannot be the only reason why there aren't more blacks and Latinos
working in Silicon Valley. The majority of jobs, such as many
professional positions in human resources, accounting, finance and
marketing, do not require a technical degree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
