<HEADLINE> Second Albright-Netanyahu Meeting Ends in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 4 (Xinhua) -- The Second meeting between U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu ended here Monday evening without any
indication that a new Middle East peace deal is under way.
</P>
<P>
Shai Bazak, Israeli government spokesman, declined to give any
details of the meeting but announced that Prime Minister Netanyahu
will have a third round of meeting with Albright Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Albright, who was locked in heated talks
with both Israeli and Palestinian leaders, was due to have a
second of meeting with Palestinian President Yasser Arafat Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said early Monday
that the United States was not optimistic that they could bridge
the significant gaps between the Palestinians and the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"Our optimism is not high based on the evidence that we've seen
so far, but we are going to continue to work at it and we very
much want these meetings to be decisive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright, whose government is striving to revive the deadlocked
Middle East peace process, early Monday held separate talks with
both Netanyahu and Arafat but failed to broker any breakthrough
between them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
