<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Helps Sri Lanka Clean Up Industrial Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 4 (Xinhua) -- A new waster-treatment
facility that Sri Lanka opened recently is expected to reduce
chemical emissions and other effluents from its leather industry
by 40 percent, according to a United Nations agency.
</P>
<P>
The project funded by the U.N. Development Fund (UNDP) uses a
simple recycling technology to recover chromium from waste water,
enabling tanneries to reuse it, the UNDP said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tanneries are among the country's worst polluters, dumping
chromium-laden water into rivers, with an estimated 800 tons of
hide-treating chromium making its way into the water system of the
South Asian country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP has been working with Sri Lanka for the past two years
to reduce the leather inustry's environmental toll while ensuring
that firms maintain their competitive edge in world markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
