<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gingrich Plans to Test Staff for Illegal Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 4 (Xinhua) -- Speaker Newt Gingrich of the
House of Representatives plans to begin testing his staff for
illegal drug use, his spokeswoman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Details are under discussion, said the spokeswoman, Christina
Martin.
</P>
<P>
Members of Congress are free to test their own staffs, but
Republican Representatives Joe Barton of Texas and Dan Burton of
Indiana are the only ones who say they do so.
</P>
<P>
Barton and retiring Republican Representative Gerald Solomon is
co-sponsoring a measure, to be introduced soon, that would require
drug testing for all House members and their staffs.
</P>
<P>
"The key will be when members start testing themselves," Barton
said through a spokeswoman. "We need to test members of Congress.
That's what the American people are waiting to see."
</P>
<P>
Gingrich's plan was first reported by the Capitol Hill
newspaper, Roll Call.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich has stepped up his criticism of the Clinton
administration for alleged failures to address the illegal
drug-use problem. At a Republican rally last week, he outlined a
broad legislative agenda against drugs.
</P>
<P>
The House has plans to vote in the next few months on a range
of anti-drug bills.  
</P>
</TEXT>
